{{HMS|Hampshire|D06|6}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/63467374@N04/5775808797/in/album-72157626716500339/|title=HMS Hampshire|author=|date=|website=flickr.com|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n:{{HMAS|Brisbane|1915|6}}\n:{{HMAS|Napier|G97|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Grays, Essex|Grays]]===\n:{{HMS|Ark Royal|1914|6}}\n:{{HMS|Berkeley Castle|K387|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bicester|L34|6}}\n:{{HMS|Carstairs|1919|6}}\n:{{HMS|Contest|R12|6}}\n:{{HMS|Foylebank}}\n:{{HMS|Hydra|J275|6}}\n:{{HMS|L2}}\n:{{HMS|Lance|G87|6}}\n:{{HMS|Laverock|1913|6}}\n:{{HMS|Liffey|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Spirit|P245|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tiverton|1918|6}}\n:{{HMS|Walpole|D41|6}}\n:{{MV|Sand Star}}\n:[[RFA Robert Dundas (A204)|RFA ''Robert Dundas'']]\n:[[RFA Sea Salvor (A503)|RFA ''Sea Salvor'']]\n:{{SS|Holdernith}}\n:[[Cutty Sark (yacht)|''Cutty Sark'']]\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]===\n:{{HMS|Dominion|1903|6}}\n:{{RMS|Etruria}}\n:{{HMS|Hind|1911|6}}\n:{{HMS|Hindustan|1903|6}}\n:{{HMS|Holderness|L48|6}}\n:{{HMS|Jed|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Nith|1905|6}}\n:{{HMS|Ribble|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Skirmisher|1905|6}}\n:{{HMS|Starfish|1895|6}}\n:{{HMS|Sutlej|1899|6}}\n:{{HMS|Swale|1905|6}}\n:{{HMS|Welland|1904|6}}\n:{{SS|Aleppo}}\n:{{SS|Staveley|1891|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Barrow-in-Furness]]===\n:{{HMS|Blencathra|L24|6}}\n:{{HMS|Dido|37|6}}\n:{{HMS|Garth|L20|6}}\n:{{HMS|Meteorite}}\n:{{HMS|Scylla|98|6}}\n:{{HMS|Southdown|L25|6}}\n:{{HMS|Whitehall}}\n:[[RFA Abbeydale (A109)|RFA ''Abbeydale'']]\n:{{SS|Baxtergate}}\n:[[TSS Duke of Clarence|TSS ''Duke of Clarence'']]\n:{{HMS|Explorer|submarine|6}}\n:{{HMS|Excalibur}}\n:{{HMS|London|69|6}}\n:{{HMAS|Australia|D84|6}}\n:{{RMS|Empress of Russia}}\n:{{SS|Bendigo}}\n:[[HMT Dongola|HMT ''Dongola'']]\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Morecambe]]===\n:{{HMS|Diadem|1896|6}}\n:{{HMS|Glasgow|1909|6}}\n:{{HMS|Imperieuse|1883|6}}\n:{{HMS|Northampton|1876|6}}\n:{{HMS|Orlando|1886|6}}\n:{{HMS|Raleigh|1873|6}}\n:{{HMS|Repulse|1892|6}}\n:{{RMS|Majestic|1889|6}}\n:{{SS|Ben-my-Chree|1875|6}}\n:{{SS|Ionic|1883|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Pembroke Dock]]===\n:{{HMS|Birmingham|1913|6}}\n:{{HMS|Chatham|1911|6}}\n:{{HMS|Leamington|1918|6}}\n:{{HMS|Southampton|1912|6}}\n:[[HMT Richard Bacon|HMT ''Richard Bacon'']]\n:[[RFA Salvestor (A499)|RFA ''Salvestor'']]\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Milford Haven]]===\n:{{HMS|Kangaroo|1900|6}}\n:{{HMS|Opportune|G80|6}}\n:{{HMS|Prince of Wales|1902|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tetcott|L99|6}}\n:{{HMS|Watchman|D26|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Lelant|Lelant or Hayle]]===\n:{{HMS|Aberdeen|L97|6}}\n:{{HMS|Acasta|1912|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bellona|1909|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bristol|1910|6}}\n:{{HMS|Chelmer|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Cockatrice|1912|6}}\n:{{HMS|Fareham|J89|6}}\n:{{HMS|Newcastle|1909|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tartar|1907|6}}\n:{{SS|Lyonesse|1889|6}}\n\n;Lizzie the elephant\nAt the outbreak of World War I, 1,235 people were on the payroll of Thomas Ward's company and a thousand tons of scrap metal per day was being fed to the country's steel makers. However, with demand so high, and many of the horses Ward had previously used to transport his goods around Sheffield conscripted by the military he had an increasingly difficult time to match supply with demand. Lizzie the Elephant was brought in as a solution to this problem.<ref name=\"shef.ac.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfa.dept.shef.ac.uk/jungle/index4d3.htmll|title=University of Sheffield project page|author=|date=|website=shef.ac.uk|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLizzie the Elephant was drafted in from Sedgwick's Menagerie, a travelling circus ran by William Sedgwick (1841\u20131927), after work horses from Thomas Ward's were sent or requisitioned to the front in the [[First World War]]. The elephant was said to be able to do the work of three of Ward's horses and soon got herself the name 'Tommy Ward's Elephant' as she became a familiar sight carrying or hauling goods around [[Sheffield]], controlled by her trainer Richard Sedgwick (1875\u20131931) (son of the circus ringleader William Sedgwick).<ref name=\"shef.ac.uk\"/> Lizzie was said to have inspired other Sheffield firms to creative means with their wartime transportation and a company in the [[Wicker]] area of the city was said to have used camels also from Sedgwick's Menagerie in place of their own horses.<ref>''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' Tuesday 18 February 2914, page 6</ref> Unfortunately, walking around the [[cobblestone]]d streets of Sheffield damaged Lizzie's feet, and although she continued to work for Ward's firm for sometime after the end of the first world war she was eventually returned to the circus.\n\nLizzie has gone down in Sheffield legend, and many stories and legends surround her adventures. She also gave name to the popular Sheffield sayings \"done up like Tommy Ward's elephant\" - meaning someone carrying much weight, and the self-explanatory \"like trying to shift Tommy Ward's elephant\". A [[Sheffield Community Transport]] bus was named \"Lizzie Ward\" after her and is an [[Optare Solo]] model.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*{{colledge}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Thomas_W._Ward Gracesguide.co.uk: Information on Thos W Ward yard]\n*[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/maritime/exhibitions/muck/ Liverpoolmuseums.org: Information on Thos W Ward company]\n*[http://www.nfa.dept.shef.ac.uk/jungle/index4d3.html Sheffield Educated - Lizzie the Elephant]\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/making_history/makhist10_prog13d.shtml Information on the elephant]\n{{Commons category|position=left|Thos W Ward Limited}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, Thos W}}\n[[Category:Ship breaking]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Sheffield]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 1982]]\n[[Category:Energy companies established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Waste management companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1982 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:1982 disestablishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:The Bailey Bridge (geograph 3669971).jpg|thumb|Bailey Bridge, erected in 2006 at the rear of Albion Works, Sheffield|alt=]]\n[[File:Field with power lines, Ketton, Rutland - geograph.org.uk - 1074132.jpg|thumb|Cement kiln 8, Ketton, Rutland]]\n'''Thos. W. Ward Ltd''' was a [[Sheffield]], Yorkshire, steel, engineering and cement business which began as coal and coke merchants then expanded to recycling metal for Sheffield's steel industry, engineering and the supply of machinery.\n\nIn 1894 as part of the scrap metal operation Ward's began to set up substantial [[Ship breaking|shipbreaking]] yards in different parts of England and in Scotland and Wales. By 1953 Thos W  Ward employed 11,500 people.\n\nWard's business was reorganised at the end of the 1970s when it moved from being an engineering group with a motley assortment of subsidiaries to being principally dependent on [[cement]]. In 1982 it was bought by [[Rio Tinto Group|RTZ]].\n\n==History==\nThis business was founded by [[Thomas William Ward (industrialist)|Thomas William Ward]] in 1878 with the name Thos. W. Ward. Ward's provided coal and coke and very soon recycling or scrap metal services then added dealing in new and used machinery related to the iron, steel, coal, engineering and allied industries and manufacturing that machinery.<ref name=TT44870>Thos. W. Ward, Limited. ''The Times'', Wednesday, 18 April 1928; pg. 23; Issue 44870</ref>\n\nWard's Constructional Engineering Department manufactured and erected steel frame buildings, bridges, collieries, steel works equipment and furnaces. The Rail Department supplied light and heavy rails, sleepers, switches and crossings and equipped complete sidings. [[De Lank Quarries]] produced the [[granite]] for [[Tower Bridge]] and [[Blackfriars Bridge]], major lighthouses and prestige buildings in London and elsewhere.<ref>Thos. W. Ward Limited Albion Works. Sheffield. ''The Times'', Wednesday, 9 May 1928; pg. 22; Issue 44888</ref>\n\n===Shipbreaking===\nIn 1894 Ward's moved into ship breaking at many different locations. A limited liability company was formed and registered 19 May 1904 to own and continue all the businesses operating under the name Thos. W. Ward.<ref name=TT46915>Thos. W. Ward Limited, Albion Works, Sheffield. ''The Times'', Monday, 19 November 1934; pg. 20; Issue 46915</ref> By 1920 when raising further capital from the public the prospectus claimed these notable facts for  Thos. W. Ward: \"Premier shipbreaking firm in the world, largest stockholders to the iron, steel and machinery trades, constructional engineers, merchants, etc.\"<ref name=TT42314>Thos. W. Ward Limited. ''The Times'', Thursday, 22 January 1920; pg. 19; Issue 42314</ref>\n\n===Portland Cement===\nNew capital was raised from the public in 1928 to establish a new [[Greenfield project|greenfield]] [[Portland cement]] business at Ketton in [[Rutland]] on 1,170 acres of freehold land with oolitic limestone and clays suitable to produce the highest quality rapid-hardening Portland cement. It was a particular project of new chairman Joseph Ward (1865-1941), brother of Thomas Ward (1853-1926).<ref name=TT44870/> [[Ketton Cement Works]] became the core activity of Ward's in the late 1970s.\n\nAfter 55 years, in 1934, when the employees numbered in excess of 4,000 people, the principal businesses were:\n*Construction, mechanical and electrical engineering manufacturers\n*Coal coke iron steel metal and machinery factors and merchants\n*Ship and works dismantlers, owners and brokers\n*Wharf owners\n*Machinery and plant valuers\n*Nut and bolt manufacturers\n*Horn handle manufacturers for cutlery\n*Brick manufacturers\n*Dry slag and tar macadam manufacturers\n*Quarry owners\n[[File:Albion Works reflection (geograph 3669975).jpg|thumb|Albion Works 2013]]\nFreehold Premises:\n:Albion Works, [[Tinsley, South Yorkshire|Tinsley]] and [[Millhouses]], [[Sheffield]]\n:and at [[Silvertown]], [[Grays]] (Essex), [[Inverkeithing]], [[Scotstoun|Glasgow]], [[Wishaw]], [[Birmingham]], [[Briton Ferry]], [[Milford Haven]], [[Lelant]], [[Silverdale, Lancashire|Silverdale]], [[Low Moor Ironworks|Low Moor (Bradford)]], Albion ([[Mansfield]]) sand quarries etc and Brickworks at [[Longton, Lancashire#Places of interest|Longton]], [[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]] and [[Apedale]]<ref name=TT46915/>\n\nLeasehold Premises:\n:Charlton Works and Effingham Road, Sheffield\n:Liverpool, Dublin, [[De Lank Quarries|Cornish Granite Quarries (De Lank)]], [[Denny, Falkirk|Denny]], Preston, Barrow-in-Furness, Pembroke Dock, [[Hayle]] and [[Scunthorpe]].<ref name=TT46915/>\n\nSubsidiaries:\n*Milford Haven Dock & Railway Company, [[Low Moor Ironworks|Low Moor Best Yorkshire Iron]], The Midland Iron Co, Pengwern and Gwydir Quarries, The Drybrook Quarries, North Lonsdale Tar Macadam.\n*The [[Ketton Cement Works|Ketton Portland Cement Co]] (controlling interest)<ref name=TT46915/>\n\n===W S Laycock===\nThis old-established business was bought in 1934. Laycock's made railway carriage and steamship fittings, underframes for locomotives and railway coaches and in 1934 also makes automobile axles, gearboxes, propellor shafts and Laycock's own Layrub flexible drive joints.<ref name=TT46915/> Two years later [[Laycock Engineering]] was sold to some investors.<ref name=TT47266>The Laycock Engineering Company, Limited. ''The Times'', Wednesday, 8 January 1936; pg. 16; Issue 47266.</ref>\n\n===1970s===\nBy 1969 the Ward group was believed to be primarily in metal supply, particularly from ship breaking, but also producing cement, supplying roadstone, providing rail sidings, building new industrial works and equipping them with the necessary plant and machinery.<ref>Tools to finish all jobs. ''The Times'', Monday, 10 November 1969; pg. V; Issue 57713.</ref>\n\n==Division==\nIn October 1981 Thos. W. Ward's was split into three:\n*Thos. W. Ward (Raw Materials) the former iron and steel division active in processing and merchanting carbon scrap, special steel scrap, non-ferrous scrap metals and steel stockholding.\n*Thos. W. Ward (Industrial Supplies)\n*Thos. W. Ward (Industrial Dismantling)<ref>Reorganization at Thos. W. Ward. ''The Times'', Saturday, 26 September 1981; pg. 24; Issue 61043</ref>\n\nWithin a short time [[Rio Tinto Group|RTZ]] began to buy a substantial shareholding and this takeover was completed in early 1982.<ref>''The Times'', Saturday, 23 January 1982; pg. 15; Issue 61139</ref> RTZ put the Ward cement operation with that of Tunnel Holdings and named the combination RTZ Cement which then had about one quarter of the UK cement market.<ref>Cement cartel resists a shake-up. ''The Times'', Thursday, 16 June 1983; pg. 19; Issue 61560</ref> The Railway Engineers department of Thos. W Ward was bought by [[Henry Boot plc|Henry Boot]].<ref>''The Times'', Thursday, 15 March 1984; pg. 19; Issue 61782</ref> RTZ sold Thos. W. Ward (Roadstone) to [[RMC Group|Ready Mixed Concrete]] in June 1988.<ref>RTZ in \u00a333m sale of aggregates firm. '' The Times'', Wednesday, 29 June 1988; pg. 26; Issue 63120</ref>\n\n==Ship and Works' dismantlers==\nWorks dismantled before 1926: Abbott's Works, Gateshead; Bowling Ironworks; Kelham Rolling Mills, Sheffield; Derwent Rolling Mills, Workington; Dearne & Dove Works; West Cumberland Whittington Works, Crawshay's Cyfarthfa Works, Bessemer's Works, Bolton; Mars Ironworks, Wolverhampton; Effingham Nut and Bolt Works, Sheffield.<ref>Obituary, Mr. T. W. Ward. ''The Times'', Wednesday, 10 February 1926; pg. 16; Issue 44192</ref>  Thos W Ward also dismantled [[The Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digital.lib.umd.edu/worldsfairs/result/id/umd:768?query=sheffield|title=Dismantling by Thos. W. Ward Ltd., Sheffield & London {{!}} World's Fair Treasury|website=digital.lib.umd.edu|access-date=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n:[[HMS Wellington (1816)|HMS ''Akbar'']]\n:{{HMS|Benbow|1885|6}}\n:{{HMS|Boadicea|1875|6}}\n:{{HMS|Centurion|1892|6}}\n:{{HMS|Colossus|1882|6}}\n:{{HMS|Devastation|1871|6}}\n:{{HMS|Edinburgh|1882|6}}\n:{{HMS|Narcissus|1886|6}}\n:{{HMS|Nile|1888|6}}\n:{{HMS|Prince Albert|1864|6}}\n:{{HMS|Sans Pareil|1887|6}}\n:{{HMS|Warspite|1884|6}}\n:{{SS|Adriatic|1871|6}}\n:{{SS|Alaska|1881|6}}\n:{{SS|Arabic|1881|6}}\n:{{SS|Britannia|1887|6}}\n:{{SS|Cleopatra}}\n:''[[Cordoba (ship)|Cordoba]]''\n:{{RMS|Etruria}}\n:{{SS|Furnessia|1880|6}}\n:{{SS|Leviathan}}\n:{{RMS|Lucania}}\n:{{SS|Majestic|1890|6}}\n:{{SS|Munchen}}\n:{{SS|Servia}}\n:{{SS|Syrian}}\n:''[[Terec]]''\n:{{SS|Vancouver}}<ref name=TT42314/>\n:{{RMS|Saragossa}}<ref name=TT39479>A review of Lloyd's Register, ''The Times'', Wednesday, 11 January 1911; pg. 21; Issue 39479</ref>\n:{{RMS|Cherbourg}}<ref name=TT39479/>\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Inverkeithing]]===\n[[File:Mauretania 2 at the breakers yard.jpg|thumb|right|The [[RMS Mauretania (1938)|RMS ''Mauretania'']] arrives at Inverkeithing ready to be broken for scrap, 1965]]\n*[[HMS Magnificent (1894)|HMS ''Magnificent'']] (1922)\n*[[HMS Dreadnought (1906)|HMS ''Dreadnought'']] (1923)\n*[[HMS Mars (1848)|HMS ''Mars'']] (1929)\n*[[SS Zeeland (1901)|SS ''Zeeland'']] (1930)\n*[[HMS Tiger (1913)|HMS ''Tiger'']] (1932)\n*[[RMS Cedric|RMS ''Cedric'']] (1932)\n*{{RMS|Olympic}} (Hull only during 1937 as superstructure was removed at [[Jarrow]] between 1935 and 1937)\n*[[RMS Majestic (1914)|RMS ''Majestic''/HMS ''Caledonia'']] (1943)\n*[[HMS Otway|HMAS/M ''Otway'']] (September 1945)\n*[[HMS Uproar (P31)|HMS/M ''Uproar'']] (February 1946)\n*[[HMS Unruly (P49)|HMS/M ''Unruly'']] (February 1946)\n*[[HMS Unsparing (P55)|HMS/M ''Unsparing'']] (14 February 1946)\n*[[HMS Revenge (06)|HMS ''Revenge'']] (1948)\n*[[HMS Royal Sovereign (05)|HMS ''Royal Sovereign'']] (1948)\n*{{HMS|Nelson|28|6}} (1949)\n*[[HMS Rodney (29)|HMS ''Rodney'']] (1949)\n*[[RMS Empress of Australia (1919)|RMS ''Empress of Australia'']] (1952)<ref>Ship Modelling Mailing List (SMML): [http://smmlonline.com/articles/empressaustralia/empressaustralia.html ''Empress of Australia'']</ref>\n*HMS Formidable (1953)\n*[[RMS Maloja|RMS ''Maloja'']] (1954)\n*{{HMS|Implacable|R86|6}} (1955)\n*{{RMS|Scythia}} (1958) \n*{{HMS|Glory|R62|6}} (1961)\n*[[MV Britannic (1929)|MV ''Britannic III'']] (1961)\n*[[HMS Thule (P325)|HMS/M ''Thule'']] (14 September 1962)\n*[[HMS Concord (R63)|HMS ''Concord'']] (22 October 1962)\n*[[RMS Mauretania (1938)|RMS ''Mauretania'' (1965)]] (second vessel to carry the name for [[Cunard Line|Cunard]])\n*[[MT Haakon Havan|MT ''Haakon Havan'']] (Renamed ''Norske Esso'') 1960\n*{{SS|Ambrose}} (1946)\n*[[HMS Hilary (1931)|SS ''Hilary'']] (1959)\n*{{HMS|Howe|32|6}}, June 1958 --> 1960/61\n*[[HMS Armada (D14)|HMS ''Armada'']] (1965)\n*[[HMS Alaric (P441)|HMS/M ''Alaric'']] (July 1971)\n*[[HMS Ambush (P418)|HMS/M ''Ambush'']] (July 1971)\n*[[HMS Anchorite (P422)|HMS/M ''Amphion'']] [became ''Anchorite'']. (July 1971)\n*{{HMS|Aisne|D22|6}} (1970)\n*[[HMS Maidstone (1937)|HMS ''Maidstone'']] (May 1978)\n*[[HMS Roberts]] (1965)\nKdF ship Robert Ley (1947)\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Briton Ferry]]===\n:{{HMS|Adventure|M23|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bellona|63|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bermuda|52|6}}\n:{{HMS|Cambrian|R85|6}}\n:{{HMS|Croome|L62|6}}\n:{{HMS|Crossbow|D96|6}}\n:{{HMS|Cumberland|1902|6}}\n:{{HMS|Dee|1903|6}}\n:{{HMS|Druid|1911|6}}\n:{{HMS|Fury|H76|6}}\n:{{HMS|Gloucester|1909|6}}\n:{{HMS|Hardy|1912|6}}\n:{{HMS|Howe|1885|6}}\n:{{HMS|Loch Dunvegan|K425|6}}\n:{{HMS|Mutine|1900|6}}\n:{{HMS|Revenge|1892|6}}\n:{{HMS|Rother|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Royal Oak|1892|6}}\n:{{HMS|Shakespeare|P221|6}}\n:{{HMS|Taciturn|P334|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tally-Ho|P317|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tempest|H71|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tenby|F65|6}}\n:{{HMS|Thrasher|N37|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tonbridge|1918|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tuna|N94|6}}\n:{{HMS|Venus|R50|6}}\n:{{HMS|Zambesi|R66|6}}\n:[[RFA Salvestor (A499)|RFA ''Salvestor'']]\n:{{SS|Empire Rest}}\n:[[ST Sea Alarm|ST ''Sea Alarm'']]\n:{{HMCS|Nene|K270|6}}\n:{{HMS|Hampshire|D06|6}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/63467374@N04/5775808797/in/album-72157626716500339/|title=HMS Hampshire|author=|date=|website=flickr.com|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n:{{HMAS|Brisbane|1915|6}}\n:{{HMAS|Napier|G97|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Grays]]===\n:{{HMS|Ark Royal|1914|6}}\n:{{HMS|Berkeley Castle|K387|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bicester|L34|6}}\n:{{HMS|Carstairs|1919|6}}\n:{{HMS|Contest|R12|6}}\n:{{HMS|Foylebank}}\n:{{HMS|Hydra|J275|6}}\n:{{HMS|L2}}\n:{{HMS|Lance|G87|6}}\n:{{HMS|Laverock|1913|6}}\n:{{HMS|Liffey|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Spirit|P245|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tiverton|1918|6}}\n:{{HMS|Walpole|D41|6}}\n:{{MV|Sand Star}}\n:[[RFA Robert Dundas (A204)|RFA ''Robert Dundas'']]\n:[[RFA Sea Salvor (A503)|RFA ''Sea Salvor'']]\n:{{SS|Holdernith}}\n:[[Cutty Sark (yacht)|''Cutty Sark'']]\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]===\n:{{HMS|Dominion|1903|6}}\n:{{RMS|Etruria}}\n:{{HMS|Hind|1911|6}}\n:{{HMS|Hindustan|1903|6}}\n:{{HMS|Holderness|L48|6}}\n:{{HMS|Jed|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Nith|1905|6}}\n:{{HMS|Ribble|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Skirmisher|1905|6}}\n:{{HMS|Starfish|1895|6}}\n:{{HMS|Sutlej|1899|6}}\n:{{HMS|Swale|1905|6}}\n:{{HMS|Welland|1904|6}}\n:{{SS|Aleppo}}\n:{{SS|Staveley|1891|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Barrow-in-Furness]]===\n:{{HMS|Blencathra|L24|6}}\n:{{HMS|Dido|37|6}}\n:{{HMS|Garth|L20|6}}\n:{{HMS|Meteorite}}\n:{{HMS|Scylla|98|6}}\n:{{HMS|Southdown|L25|6}}\n:{{HMS|Whitehall}}\n:[[RFA Abbeydale (A109)|RFA ''Abbeydale'']]\n:{{SS|Baxtergate}}\n:[[TSS Duke of Clarence|TSS ''Duke of Clarence'']]\n:{{HMS|Explorer|submarine|6}}\n:{{HMS|Excalibur}}\n:{{HMS|London|69|6}}\n:{{HMAS|Australia|D84|6}}\n:{{RMS|Empress of Russia}}\n:{{SS|Bendigo}}\n:[[HMT Dongola|HMT ''Dongola'']]\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Morecambe]]===\n:{{HMS|Diadem|1896|6}}\n:{{HMS|Glasgow|1909|6}}\n:{{HMS|Imperieuse|1883|6}}\n:{{HMS|Northampton|1876|6}}\n:{{HMS|Orlando|1886|6}}\n:{{HMS|Raleigh|1873|6}}\n:{{HMS|Repulse|1892|6}}\n:{{RMS|Majestic|1889|6}}\n:{{SS|Ben-my-Chree|1875|6}}\n:{{SS|Ionic|1883|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Pembroke Dock]]===\n:{{HMS|Birmingham|1913|6}}\n:{{HMS|Chatham|1911|6}}\n:{{HMS|Leamington|1918|6}}\n:{{HMS|Southampton|1912|6}}\n:[[HMT Richard Bacon|HMT ''Richard Bacon'']]\n:[[RFA Salvestor (A499)|RFA ''Salvestor'']]\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Milford Haven]]===\n:{{HMS|Kangaroo|1900|6}}\n:{{HMS|Opportune|G80|6}}\n:{{HMS|Prince of Wales|1902|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tetcott|L99|6}}\n:{{HMS|Watchman|D26|6}}\n\n===List of ships broken up at [[Lelant|Lelant or Hayle]]===\n:{{HMS|Aberdeen|L97|6}}\n:{{HMS|Acasta|1912|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bellona|1909|6}}\n:{{HMS|Bristol|1910|6}}\n:{{HMS|Chelmer|1904|6}}\n:{{HMS|Cockatrice|1912|6}}\n:{{HMS|Fareham|J89|6}}\n:{{HMS|Newcastle|1909|6}}\n:{{HMS|Tartar|1907|6}}\n:{{SS|Lyonesse|1889|6}}\n\n;Lizzie the elephant\nAt the outbreak of World War I, 1,235 people were on the payroll of Thomas Ward's company and a thousand tons of scrap metal per day was being fed to the country's steel makers. However, with demand so high, and many of the horses Ward had previously used to transport his goods around Sheffield conscripted by the military he had an increasingly difficult time to match supply with demand. Lizzie the Elephant was brought in as a solution to this problem.<ref name=\"shef.ac.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfa.dept.shef.ac.uk/jungle/index4d3.htmll|title=University of Sheffield project page|author=|date=|website=shef.ac.uk|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLizzie the Elephant was drafted in from Sedgwick's Menagerie, a travelling circus ran by William Sedgwick (1841\u20131927), after work horses from Thomas Ward's were sent or requisitioned to the front in the [[First World War]]. The elephant was said to be able to do the work of three of Ward's horses and soon got herself the name 'Tommy Ward's Elephant' as she became a familiar sight carrying or hauling goods around [[Sheffield]], controlled by her trainer Richard Sedgwick (1875\u20131931) (son of the circus ringleader William Sedgwick).<ref name=\"shef.ac.uk\"/> Lizzie was said to have inspired other Sheffield firms to creative means with their wartime transportation and a company in the [[Wicker]] area of the city was said to have used camels also from Sedgwick's Menagerie in place of their own horses.<ref>''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' Tuesday 18 February 2914, page 6</ref> Unfortunately, walking around the [[cobblestone]]d streets of Sheffield damaged Lizzie's feet, and although she continued to work for Ward's firm for sometime after the end of the first world war she was eventually returned to the circus.\n\nLizzie has gone down in Sheffield legend, and many stories and legends surround her adventures. She also gave name to the popular Sheffield sayings \"done up like Tommy Ward's elephant\" - meaning someone carrying much weight, and the self-explanatory \"like trying to shift Tommy Ward's elephant\". A [[Sheffield Community Transport]] bus was named \"Lizzie Ward\" after her and is an [[Optare Solo]] model.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*{{colledge}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Thomas_W._Ward Gracesguide.co.uk: Information on Thos W Ward yard]\n*[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/maritime/exhibitions/muck/ Liverpoolmuseums.org: Information on Thos W Ward company]\n*[http://www.nfa.dept.shef.ac.uk/jungle/index4d3.html Sheffield Educated - Lizzie the Elephant]\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/history/making_history/makhist10_prog13d.shtml Information on the elephant]\n{{Commons category|position=left|Thos W Ward Limited}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, Thos W}}\n[[Category:Ship breaking]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Sheffield]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 1982]]\n[[Category:Energy companies established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Waste management companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1982 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:1982 disestablishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrays(link changed toGrays, Essex; link changed toGrays, Essex) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thos_W_Ward"}
{"title_page": "April 14", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[43 BC]] &ndash; [[Battle of Forum Gallorum]]: [[Mark Antony]], besieging [[Julius Caesar|Caesar]]'s assassin [[Decimus Junius Brutus Albinus|Decimus Brutus]] in [[Mutina]], defeats the forces of the consul [[Gaius Vibius Pansa Caetronianus|Pansa]], but is then immediately defeated by the army of the other consul, [[Aulus Hirtius]].<ref name=\"SpoffordWeitenkampf1906\">{{cite book|author1=Ainsworth Rand Spofford|author2=Frank Weitenkampf|author3=John Porter Lamberton|title=The library of historic characters and famous events of all nations and all ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljxIAQAAIAAJ|year=1906|publisher=J.B. Millet|page=99}}</ref>\n*[[AD 69]] &ndash; [[Vitellius]], commander of the [[Rhine]] armies, defeats [[Roman emperor|Emperor]] [[Otho]] in the [[Battle of Bedriacum]] to take power over Rome.<ref>{{cite book|author=E. T. Salmon|title=A History of the Roman World: From 30 BC to AD 138|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bQ6AAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA204|date=21 August 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-96341-6|pages=204}}</ref>\n*[[AD 70]] &ndash; [[Siege of Jerusalem (AD 70)|Siege of Jerusalem]]: [[Titus]], son of emperor [[Vespasian]], surrounds the Jewish capital with four [[Roman legion]]s.\n* [[193]] &ndash; [[Septimius Severus]] is proclaimed [[Roman emperor]] by the army in [[Illyricum (Roman province)|Illyricum]] (in the [[Balkans]]).\n* [[966]] &ndash; After his marriage to the Christian [[Doubravka of Bohemia]], the [[paganism|pagan]] ruler of the [[Polans (western)|Polans]], [[Mieszko I of Poland|Mieszko&nbsp;I]], [[Baptism of Poland|converts to Christianity]], an event considered to be the [[History of Poland during the Piast dynasty|founding of the Polish state]].\n* [[972]] &ndash; Co-Emperor [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto II]], a son of [[Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto I]] (the Great), marries the Byzantine princess [[Theophanu]]. She is crowned empress by Pope [[Pope John XIII|John XIII]] at [[Rome]].\n*[[1028]] &ndash; [[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry III]], son of [[Conrad II, Holy Roman Emperor|Conrad]], is elected [[King of Germany]].\n*[[1205]] &ndash; [[Battle of Adrianople (1205)|Battle of Adrianople]] between [[Bulgarians]] and [[Crusaders]].\n*[[1294]] &ndash; [[Tem\u00fcr Khan|Tem\u00fcr]], grandson of [[Kublai]], is elected [[Khagan]] of the [[Mongols]] and Emperor of the [[Yuan dynasty]] with the reigning titles Oljeitu and Chengzong.\n*[[1341]] &ndash; Sack of [[Saluzzo]] (Italy) by Italian-Angevine troops under [[Manfred V, Marquess of Saluzzo]].\n*[[1434]] &ndash; The foundation stone of [[Nantes Cathedral]], France is laid.\n*[[1471]] &ndash; In England, the [[Yorkists]] under [[Edward IV of England|Edward IV]] defeat the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrians]] under the [[Richard Neville, 16th Earl of Warwick|Earl of Warwick]] at the [[Battle of Barnet]]; the Earl is killed and [[Edward IV]] resumes the throne.\n*[[1561]] &ndash; A [[1561 celestial phenomenon over Nuremberg|celestial phenomenon]] is reported over Nuremberg, described as an aerial battle.\n*[[1639]] &ndash; Imperial forces are defeated by the Swedes at the [[Battle of Chemnitz]]. The Swedish victory prolongs the [[Thirty Years' War]] and allows them to advance into [[Bohemia]].\n*[[1699]] &ndash; [[Khalsa]]: The [[Sikh]] religion was formalised as the [[Khalsa]] - the brotherhood of Warrior-Saints - by [[Guru Gobind Singh]] in northern India, in accordance with the [[Nanakshahi calendar]].\n*[[1775]] &ndash; The first [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolition]] society in North America is established. The [[Pennsylvania Abolition Society|Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage]] is organized in [[Philadelphia]] by [[Benjamin Franklin]] and [[Benjamin Rush]].\n*[[1816]] &ndash; [[Bussa]], a slave in British-ruled [[Barbados]], leads a slave rebellion and is killed. For this, he is remembered as the first national hero of [[Barbados]].\n*[[1828]] &ndash; [[Noah Webster]] copyrights the first edition of [[Webster's Dictionary|his dictionary]].\n*[[1849]] &ndash; Hungary [[Hungarian Declaration of Independence|declares itself independent]] of [[Austrian Empire|Austria]] with [[Lajos Kossuth]] as its leader.\n*[[1865]] &ndash; U.S. President [[Abraham Lincoln]] is [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|shot]] in [[Ford's Theatre]] by [[John Wilkes Booth]]; Lincoln died the next day. \n*  1865   &ndash; [[United States Secretary of State|U.S. Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] and his family are attacked at home by [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]].\n*[[1881]] &ndash; The [[Four Dead in Five Seconds Gunfight]] is fought in [[El Paso, Texas]].\n*[[1890]] &ndash; The [[Pan-American Union]] is founded by the First [[International Conference of American States]] in Washington, D.C.\n*[[1894]] &ndash; The first ever commercial [[film|motion picture]] house opened in New York City using ten [[Kinetoscope]]s, a device for peep-show viewing of films.\n*[[1900]] &ndash; The [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle]] begins.\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[James Cash Penney]] opens his [[J. C. Penney|first store]] in [[Kemmerer, Wyoming]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://shsmo.org/historicmissourians/name/p/penney/ |title=J. C. Penney |website=Historic Missourians |publisher=State Historical Society of Missouri |access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref>\n*[[1906]] &ndash; The [[Azusa Street Revival]] opens and will launch [[Pentecostalism]] as a worldwide movement.\n*[[1908]] &ndash; [[Hauser Dam]], a [[steel dam]] on the [[Missouri River]] in [[Montana]], U.S., fails, sending a surge of water {{convert|25|to|30|ft}} high downstream.\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Adana massacre|A massacre]] is organized by the [[Ottoman Empire]] against the Armenian population of [[Cilicia]].\n*[[1912]] &ndash; The British passenger liner {{RMS|Titanic}} hits an iceberg in the North Atlantic at 23:40 (sinks morning of April 15th).\n*[[1927]] &ndash; The first [[Volvo]] car premieres in [[Gothenburg]], Sweden.\n*[[1928]] &ndash; The [[Bremen (aircraft)|Bremen]], a German [[Junkers W 33]] type aircraft, reaches [[Greenly Island, Canada]] - the first successful transatlantic aeroplane flight from east to west.\n*[[1931]] &ndash; The [[Cortes Generales|Spanish Cortes]] deposes King [[Alfonso XIII of Spain|Alfonso XIII]] and proclaims the [[Second Spanish Republic]].\n*[[1935]] &ndash; The [[Black Sunday (storm)|Black Sunday dust storm]], considered one of the worst storms of the [[Dust Bowl]], swept across the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles and neighboring areas.\n*[[1939]] &ndash; ''[[The Grapes of Wrath]]'', by American author [[John Steinbeck]] is first published by the [[Viking Press]].\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[Royal Marines]] land in [[Namsos]], Norway in preparation for a larger force to arrive two days later.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; World War II: German general [[Erwin Rommel]] attacks [[Siege of Tobruk|Tobruk]].\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[1944 Bombay explosion|Bombay explosion]]: A massive explosion in [[Bombay]] harbor kills 300 and causes economic damage valued then at 20&nbsp;million pounds.\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Razing of Friesoythe]]: The [[4th Canadian (Armoured) Division]] [[Razing of Friesoythe|deliberately destroyed]] the German town of [[Friesoythe]] on the orders of [[Major general|Major General]] [[Christopher Vokes]].\n*[[1958]] &ndash; The [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] satellite [[Sputnik 2]] falls from orbit after a mission duration of 162 days. This was the first spacecraft to carry a living animal, a [[Soviet space dogs|female dog]] named [[Laika]], who likely lived only a few hours.\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Gnassingb\u00e9 Eyad\u00e9ma]] overthrows [[President of Togo]] [[Nicolas Grunitzky]] and installs himself as the new president, a title he would hold for the next 38 years.\n*[[1970]] &ndash; the [[Apollo 13]] mission suffers a near-catastrophic failure (\"[[Houston, we have a problem]]\").\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[1978 Tbilisi Demonstrations|Tbilisi Demonstrations]]: Thousands of [[Georgia (country)|Georgians]] demonstrate against Soviet attempts to change the constitutional status of the [[Georgian language]].\n*[[1981]] &ndash; [[STS-1]]: The first operational [[Space Shuttle]], ''[[Space Shuttle Columbia|Columbia]]'' completes its first test flight.\n*[[1986]] &ndash; The heaviest [[hailstone]]s ever recorded ({{convert|1|kg|lb}}) fall on the [[Gopalganj District, Bangladesh|Gopalganj district of Bangladesh]], killing 92.\n*[[1988]] &ndash; The {{USS|Samuel B. Roberts|FFG-58|6}} strikes a [[naval mine|mine]] in the [[Persian Gulf]] during [[Operation Earnest Will]].\n*  1988   &ndash; In a [[United Nations]] ceremony in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], the [[Soviet Union]] signs an agreement pledging to withdraw its troops from [[Afghanistan]].\n*[[1991]] &ndash; The [[Georgia (country)|Republic of Georgia]] introduces the post of [[President of Georgia|President]] after its declaration of independence from the Soviet Union.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; In a U.S. [[friendly fire]] incident during [[Operation Provide Comfort]] in northern [[Iraq]], two [[United States Air Force]] aircraft mistakenly [[1994 Black Hawk shootdown incident|shoot-down]] two United States Army helicopters, killing 26 people.\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[NATO]] mistakenly bombs a convoy of ethnic [[Albania]]n refugees. [[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] officials say 75 people were killed.\n*  1999   &ndash; A [[1999 Sydney hailstorm|severe hailstorm]] strikes Sydney, Australia causing [[Australian dollar|A$]]2.3&nbsp;billion in insured damages, the most costly natural disaster in Australian history.\n*[[2002]] &ndash; [[Venezuela]]n President [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] returns to office two days after being ousted and arrested by the country's military.\n*[[2003]] &ndash; The [[Human Genome Project]] is completed with 99% of the human [[genome]] sequenced to an accuracy of 99.99%.\n*  2003   &ndash; U.S. troops in [[Baghdad]] capture [[Abu Abbas]], leader of the [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] group that killed an American on the hijacked cruise liner the {{MS|Achille Lauro}} in [[1985]].\n*[[2005]] &ndash; The [[Oregon Supreme Court]] nullifies marriage licenses issued to same-sex couples a year earlier by [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]].\n*[[2006]] &ndash; Twin blasts triggered by crude bombs during [[Asr prayer]] in [[Jama Masjid, Delhi]] injure 13 people.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/14/world/blasts-at-famous-india-mosque-injure-13.html][https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Terror-Friday-Twin-blasts-rock-Delhis-Jama-Masjid/articleshow/1490834.cms][https://en.wikinews.org/wiki/Explosion_rocks_Jama_Masjid_in_India][https://www.rediff.com/news/2006/apr/14masjid.htm Two blasts rock Delhi's Jama Masjid]</ref> \n*[[2010]] &ndash; Nearly 2,700 are killed in a [[2010 Yushu earthquake|magnitude 6.9 earthquake]] in the [[Yushu Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture]].\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[April 2014 Abuja bombing|Twin bomb blasts]] in [[Abuja|Abuja, Nigeria]], kill at least 75 people and injures 141 others.\n*  2014   &ndash; Two hundred seventy-six schoolgirls are [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping|abducted]] by [[Boko Haram]] in [[Chibok]],  [[Nigeria]].\n*[[2016]] &ndash; In Japan, the [[2016 Kumamoto earthquakes#April 14 Foreshock|foreshock]] of Kumamoto earthquakes occurs.\n\n==Births==\n*[[1126]] &ndash; [[Averroes]], Spanish physician and philosopher (d. 1198)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/10/day-1198-islamic-philosopher-averroes-dies-marrakech/|title=On this day in 1198: the Islamic philosopher Averro\u00ebs dies in Marrakech|date=10 December 2017|author=Dominic Selwood|website=The Telegraph|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[1204]] &ndash; [[Henry I of Castile|Henry I]], king of [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]] (d. 1217)<ref>{{cite book|author=E. Michael Gerli|title=Medieval Iberia: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=euVJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|date=4 December 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-77162-0|pages=299}}</ref>\n*[[1331]] &ndash; [[Jeanne-Marie de Maille]], French Roman Catholic saint (d. 1414)\n*[[1527]] &ndash; [[Abraham Ortelius]], Flemish cartographer and geographer (d. 1598)\n*[[1572]] &ndash; [[Adam Tanner (mathematician)|Adam Tanner]], Austrian mathematician, philosopher, and academic (d. 1632)\n*[[1578]] &ndash; [[Philip III of Spain]] (d. 1621)<ref>{{cite book|author=Herbert Norris|title=Tudor Costume and Fashion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yVdfZGj6NmkC&pg=PA677|date=1 January 1997|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-29845-0|pages=677}}</ref>\n*[[1629]] &ndash; [[Christiaan Huygens]], Dutch mathematician, astronomer, and physicist (d. 1695)<ref>{{cite book|author=John Gribbin|title=Q is for Quantum: An Encyclopedia of Particle Physics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zBsDkgI1uQsC&pg=PA181|date=22 February 2000|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-684-86315-3|pages=181}}</ref>\n*[[1668]] &ndash; [[Magnus Julius De la Gardie]], Swedish general and politician (d. 1741)\n*[[1678]] &ndash; [[Abraham Darby I]], English iron master (d. 1717)\n*[[1709]] &ndash; [[Charles Coll\u00e9]], French playwright and songwriter (d. 1783)\n*[[1714]] &ndash; [[Adam Gib]], Scottish minister and author (d. 1788)\n*[[1738]] &ndash; [[William Cavendish-Bentinck, 3rd Duke of Portland]], English politician, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1809)\n*[[1741]] &ndash; [[Emperor Momozono]] of Japan (d. 1762)\n*[[1769]] &ndash; [[Barth\u00e9lemy Catherine Joubert]], French general (d. 1799)\n*[[1773]] &ndash; [[Jean-Baptiste de Vill\u00e8le]], French politician, 6th [[Prime Minister of France]] (d. 1854)\n*[[1788]] &ndash; [[David G. Burnet]], American politician, 2nd [[President of the Republic of Texas|Vice-President of Texas]] (d. 1870)\n*[[1800]] &ndash; [[John Appold]], English engineer (d. 1865)\n*[[1812]] &ndash; [[George Grey]], Portuguese-New Zealand soldier, explorer, and politician, 11th [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] (d. 1898)\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[Dimitri Kipiani]], Georgian publicist and author (d. 1887)\n*[[1819]] &ndash; [[Harriett Ellen Grannis Arey]], American educator, author, editor, and publisher (d. 1901)<ref name=\"Herringshaw1904\">{{cite book|last=Herringshaw|first=Thomas William|title=Herringshaw's Encyclopedia of American Biography of the Nineteenth Century: Accurate and Succinct Biographies of Famous Men and Women in All Walks of Life who are Or Have Been the Acknowledged Leaders of Life and Thought of the United States Since Its Formation ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xxg7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA50|edition=Public domain|year=1904|publisher=American Publishers' Association|pages=50\u2013}}</ref>\n*[[1827]] &ndash; [[Augustus Pitt Rivers]], English general, ethnologist, and archaeologist (d. 1900)\n*[[1852]] &ndash; [[Alexander Greenlaw Hamilton]], Australian biologist (d. 1941)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[Martin Lipp]], Estonian pastor and poet (d. 1923)\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Princess Beatrice of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1944)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Alfred Hoare Powell]], English architect, and designer and painter of pottery (d. 1960)\n*[[1866]] &ndash; [[Anne Sullivan]], American educator (d. 1936)\n*[[1868]] &ndash; [[Peter Behrens]], German architect, designed the [[AEG turbine factory]] (d. 1940)\n*[[1870]] &ndash; [[Victor Borisov-Musatov]], Russian painter and educator (d. 1905)\n*  1870   &ndash; [[Syd Gregory]], Australian cricketer and coach (d. 1929)\n*[[1872]] &ndash; [[Abdullah Yusuf Ali]], Indian-English scholar and translator (d. 1953)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Husain Salaahuddin]], Maldivian poet and scholar (d. 1948)\n*[[1882]] &ndash; [[Moritz Schlick]], German-Austrian physicist and philosopher (d. 1936)\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Ernst Robert Curtius]], German philologist and scholar (d. 1956)\n*  1886   &ndash; [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d T\u00f3th]], Hungarian poet and translator (d. 1928)\n*[[1889]] &ndash; [[Arnold J. Toynbee]], English historian and academic (d. 1975)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[B. R. Ambedkar]], Indian economist, jurist, and politician, 1st [[Minister of Law and Justice (India)|Indian Minister of Law and Justice]] (d. 1956)\n*  1891   &ndash; [[Otto Lasanen]], Finnish wrestler (d. 1958)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Juan Belmonte]], Spanish bullfighter (d. 1962)\n*  1892   &ndash; [[V. Gordon Childe]], Australian archaeologist and philologist (d. 1957)<ref>{{cite book|author=Sally Green|title=Prehistorian: A Biography of V. Gordon Childe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GeUZAAAAYAAJ|year=1981|publisher=Moonraker|page=1}}</ref>\n*  1892   &ndash; [[Claire Windsor]], American actress (d. 1972)\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[Sylvio Mantha]], Canadian ice hockey player, coach, and referee (d. 1974)\n*[[1903]] &ndash; [[Henry Corbin]], French philosopher and academic (d. 1978)\n*  1903   &ndash; [[Ruth Svedberg]], Swedish discus thrower and triathlete (d. 2002)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[John Gielgud]], English actor, director, and producer (d. 2000)<ref>{{cite book|author=Gyles Daubeney Brandreth|title=John Gielgud: a celebration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0itaAAAAMAAJ|year=1984|publisher=Pavilion|isbn=978-0-907516-38-5|page=12}}</ref>\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[Elizabeth Huckaby]], American author and educator (d. 1999)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Georg Lammers]], German sprinter (d. 1987)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Jean Pierre-Bloch]], French author and activist (d. 1999)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Faisal of Saudi Arabia]], Saudi Arabian king (d. 1975)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Duvalier]], Haitian physician and politician, 40th [[President of Haiti]] (d. 1971)<ref>{{cite book|author=Frank J. Coppa|title=Encyclopedia of Modern Dictators: From Napoleon to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gTv99LBYSL4C&pg=PA84|yea