ya/Odia]] New Year, or [[Pana Sankranti]] ([[India|India's]] [[Odisha]] state)\n**[[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] New Year, or [[Sinhala new year|Aluth Avurudhu]] ([[Sri Lanka]])\n**[[Tamil people|Tamil]] New Year, or [[Puthandu]] ([[India|India's]] [[Tamil Nadu]] state)\n**[[Thai culture|Thai]] New Year, or [[Songkran]], celebrated from [[13 April|13]] to 15 April ([[Thailand]])\n**[[Tuluva]] New Year, or [[Bisu (festival)|Bisu]] ([[India|India's]] [[Karnataka]] state)\n*The first day of [[Takayama Festival|Takayama Spring Festival]] ([[Takayama, Gifu]], Japan)\n*[[Youth Day (Angola)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/14 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=04|day=14}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/April_14 Today in Canadian History]\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:April]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[43 BC]] &ndash; [[Battle of Forum Gallorum]]: [[Mark Antony]], besieging [[Julius Caesar|Caesar]]'s assassin [[Decimus Junius Brutus Albinus|Decimus Brutus]] in [[Mutina]], defeats the forces of the consul [[Gaius Vibius Pansa Caetronianus|Pansa]], but is then immediately defeated by the army of the other consul, [[Aulus Hirtius]].<ref name=\"SpoffordWeitenkampf1906\">{{cite book|author1=Ainsworth Rand Spofford|author2=Frank Weitenkampf|author3=John Porter Lamberton|title=The library of historic characters and famous events of all nations and all ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ljxIAQAAIAAJ|year=1906|publisher=J.B. Millet|page=99}}</ref>\n*[[AD 69]] &ndash; [[Vitellius]], commander of the [[Rhine]] armies, defeats [[Roman emperor|Emperor]] [[Otho]] in the [[Battle of Bedriacum]] to take power over Rome.<ref>{{cite book|author=E. T. Salmon|title=A History of the Roman World: From 30 BC to AD 138|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bQ6AAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA204|date=21 August 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-96341-6|pages=204}}</ref>\n*[[AD 70]] &ndash; [[Siege of Jerusalem (AD 70)|Siege of Jerusalem]]: [[Titus]], son of emperor [[Vespasian]], surrounds the Jewish capital with four [[Roman legion]]s.\n* [[193]] &ndash; [[Septimius Severus]] is proclaimed [[Roman emperor]] by the army in [[Illyricum (Roman province)|Illyricum]] (in the [[Balkans]]).\n* [[966]] &ndash; After his marriage to the Christian [[Doubravka of Bohemia]], the [[paganism|pagan]] ruler of the [[Polans (western)|Polans]], [[Mieszko I of Poland|Mieszko&nbsp;I]], [[Baptism of Poland|converts to Christianity]], an event considered to be the [[History of Poland during the Piast dynasty|founding of the Polish state]].\n* [[972]] &ndash; Co-Emperor [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto II]], a son of [[Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto I]] (the Great), marries the Byzantine princess [[Theophanu]]. She is crowned empress by Pope [[Pope John XIII|John XIII]] at [[Rome]].\n*[[1028]] &ndash; [[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry III]], son of [[Conrad II, Holy Roman Emperor|Conrad]], is elected [[King of Germany]].\n*[[1205]] &ndash; [[Battle of Adrianople (1205)|Battle of Adrianople]] between [[Bulgarians]] and [[Crusaders]].\n*[[1294]] &ndash; [[Tem\u00fcr Khan|Tem\u00fcr]], grandson of [[Kublai]], is elected [[Khagan]] of the [[Mongols]] and Emperor of the [[Yuan dynasty]] with the reigning titles Oljeitu and Chengzong.\n*[[1341]] &ndash; Sack of [[Saluzzo]] (Italy) by Italian-Angevine troops under [[Manfred V, Marquess of Saluzzo]].\n*[[1434]] &ndash; The foundation stone of [[Nantes Cathedral]], France is laid.\n*[[1471]] &ndash; In England, the [[Yorkists]] under [[Edward IV of England|Edward IV]] defeat the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrians]] under the [[Richard Neville, 16th Earl of Warwick|Earl of Warwick]] at the [[Battle of Barnet]]; the Earl is killed and [[Edward IV]] resumes the throne.\n*[[1561]] &ndash; A [[1561 celestial phenomenon over Nuremberg|celestial phenomenon]] is reported over Nuremberg, described as an aerial battle.\n*[[1639]] &ndash; Imperial forces are defeated by the Swedes at the [[Battle of Chemnitz]]. The Swedish victory prolongs the [[Thirty Years' War]] and allows them to advance into [[Bohemia]].\n*[[1699]] &ndash; [[Khalsa]]: The [[Sikh]] religion was formalised as the [[Khalsa]] - the brotherhood of Warrior-Saints - by [[Guru Gobind Singh]] in northern India, in accordance with the [[Nanakshahi calendar]].\n*[[1775]] &ndash; The first [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolition]] society in North America is established. The [[Pennsylvania Abolition Society|Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage]] is organized in [[Philadelphia]] by [[Benjamin Franklin]] and [[Benjamin Rush]].\n*[[1816]] &ndash; [[Bussa]], a slave in British-ruled [[Barbados]], leads a slave rebellion and is killed. For this, he is remembered as the first national hero of [[Barbados]].\n*[[1828]] &ndash; [[Noah Webster]] copyrights the first edition of [[Webster's Dictionary|his dictionary]].\n*[[1849]] &ndash; Hungary [[Hungarian Declaration of Independence|declares itself independent]] of [[Austrian Empire|Austria]] with [[Lajos Kossuth]] as its leader.\n*[[1865]] &ndash; U.S. President [[Abraham Lincoln]] is [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|shot]] in [[Ford's Theatre]] by [[John Wilkes Booth]]; Lincoln died the next day. \n*  1865   &ndash; [[United States Secretary of State|U.S. Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] and his family are attacked at home by [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]].\n*[[1881]] &ndash; The [[Four Dead in Five Seconds Gunfight]] is fought in [[El Paso, Texas]].\n*[[1890]] &ndash; The [[Pan-American Union]] is founded by the First [[International Conference of American States]] in Washington, D.C.\n*[[1894]] &ndash; The first ever commercial [[film|motion picture]] house opened in New York City using ten [[Kinetoscope]]s, a device for peep-show viewing of films.\n*[[1900]] &ndash; The [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle]] begins.\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[James Cash Penney]] opens his [[J. C. Penney|first store]] in [[Kemmerer, Wyoming]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://shsmo.org/historicmissourians/name/p/penney/ |title=J. C. Penney |website=Historic Missourians |publisher=State Historical Society of Missouri |access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref>\n*[[1906]] &ndash; The [[Azusa Street Revival]] opens and will launch [[Pentecostalism]] as a worldwide movement.\n*[[1908]] &ndash; [[Hauser Dam]], a [[steel dam]] on the [[Missouri River]] in [[Montana]], U.S., fails, sending a surge of water {{convert|25|to|30|ft}} high downstream.\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Adana massacre|A massacre]] is organized by the [[Ottoman Empire]] against the Armenian population of [[Cilicia]].\n*[[1912]] &ndash; The British passenger liner {{RMS|Titanic}} hits an iceberg in the North Atlantic at 23:40 (sinks morning of April 15th).\n*[[1927]] &ndash; The first [[Volvo]] car premieres in [[Gothenburg]], Sweden.\n*[[1928]] &ndash; The [[Bremen (aircraft)|Bremen]], a German [[Junkers W 33]] type aircraft, reaches [[Greenly Island, Canada]] - the first successful transatlantic aeroplane flight from east to west.\n*[[1931]] &ndash; The [[Cortes Generales|Spanish Cortes]] deposes King [[Alfonso XIII of Spain|Alfonso XIII]] and proclaims the [[Second Spanish Republic]].\n*[[1935]] &ndash; The [[Black Sunday (storm)|Black Sunday dust storm]], considered one of the worst storms of the [[Dust Bowl]], swept across the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles and neighboring areas.\n*[[1939]] &ndash; ''[[The Grapes of Wrath]]'', by American author [[John Steinbeck]] is first published by the [[Viking Press]].\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[Royal Marines]] land in [[Namsos]], Norway in preparation for a larger force to arrive two days later.\n*[[1941]] &ndash; World War II: German general [[Erwin Rommel]] attacks [[Siege of Tobruk|Tobruk]].\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[1944 Bombay explosion|Bombay explosion]]: A massive explosion in [[Bombay]] harbor kills 300 and causes economic damage valued then at 20&nbsp;million pounds.\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[Razing of Friesoythe]]: The [[4th Canadian (Armoured) Division]] [[Razing of Friesoythe|deliberately destroyed]] the German town of [[Friesoythe]] on the orders of [[Major general|Major General]] [[Christopher Vokes]].\n*[[1958]] &ndash; The [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] satellite [[Sputnik 2]] falls from orbit after a mission duration of 162 days. This was the first spacecraft to carry a living animal, a [[Soviet space dogs|female dog]] named [[Laika]], who likely lived only a few hours.\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Gnassingb\u00e9 Eyad\u00e9ma]] overthrows [[President of Togo]] [[Nicolas Grunitzky]] and installs himself as the new president, a title he would hold for the next 38 years.\n*[[1970]] &ndash; the [[Apollo 13]] mission suffers a near-catastrophic problem (\"[[Houston, we have a problem]]\").\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[1978 Tbilisi Demonstrations|Tbilisi Demonstrations]]: Thousands of [[Georgia (country)|Georgians]] demonstrate against Soviet attempts to change the constitutional status of the [[Georgian language]].\n*[[1981]] &ndash; [[STS-1]]: The first operational [[Space Shuttle]], ''[[Space Shuttle Columbia|Columbia]]'' completes its first test flight.\n*[[1986]] &ndash; The heaviest [[hailstone]]s ever recorded ({{convert|1|kg|lb}}) fall on the [[Gopalganj District, Bangladesh|Gopalganj district of Bangladesh]], killing 92.\n*[[1988]] &ndash; The {{USS|Samuel B. Roberts|FFG-58|6}} strikes a [[naval mine|mine]] in the [[Persian Gulf]] during [[Operation Earnest Will]].\n*  1988   &ndash; In a [[United Nations]] ceremony in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], the [[Soviet Union]] signs an agreement pledging to withdraw its troops from [[Afghanistan]].\n*[[1991]] &ndash; The [[Georgia (country)|Republic of Georgia]] introduces the post of [[President of Georgia|President]] after its declaration of independence from the Soviet Union.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; In a U.S. [[friendly fire]] incident during [[Operation Provide Comfort]] in northern [[Iraq]], two [[United States Air Force]] aircraft mistakenly [[1994 Black Hawk shootdown incident|shoot-down]] two United States Army helicopters, killing 26 people.\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[NATO]] mistakenly bombs a convoy of ethnic [[Albania]]n refugees. [[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] officials say 75 people were killed.\n*  1999   &ndash; A [[1999 Sydney hailstorm|severe hailstorm]] strikes Sydney, Australia causing [[Australian dollar|A$]]2.3&nbsp;billion in insured damages, the most costly natural disaster in Australian history.\n*[[2002]] &ndash; [[Venezuela]]n President [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] returns to office two days after being ousted and arrested by the country's military.\n*[[2003]] &ndash; The [[Human Genome Project]] is completed with 99% of the human [[genome]] sequenced to an accuracy of 99.99%.\n*  2003   &ndash; U.S. troops in [[Baghdad]] capture [[Abu Abbas]], leader of the [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] group that killed an American on the hijacked cruise liner the {{MS|Achille Lauro}} in [[1985]].\n*[[2005]] &ndash; The [[Oregon Supreme Court]] nullifies marriage licenses issued to same-sex couples a year earlier by [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]].\n*[[2006]] &ndash; Twin blasts triggered by crude bombs during [[Asr prayer]] in [[Jama Masjid, Delhi]] injure 13 people.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/14/world/blasts-at-famous-india-mosque-injure-13.html][https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Terror-Friday-Twin-blasts-rock-Delhis-Jama-Masjid/articleshow/1490834.cms][https://en.wikinews.org/wiki/Explosion_rocks_Jama_Masjid_in_India][https://www.rediff.com/news/2006/apr/14masjid.htm Two blasts rock Delhi's Jama Masjid]</ref> \n*[[2010]] &ndash; Nearly 2,700 are killed in a [[2010 Yushu earthquake|magnitude 6.9 earthquake]] in the [[Yushu Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture]].\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[April 2014 Abuja bombing|Twin bomb blasts]] in [[Abuja|Abuja, Nigeria]], kill at least 75 people and injures 141 others.\n*  2014   &ndash; Two hundred seventy-six schoolgirls are [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping|abducted]] by [[Boko Haram]] in [[Chibok]],  [[Nigeria]].\n*[[2016]] &ndash; In Japan, the [[2016 Kumamoto earthquakes#April 14 Foreshock|foreshock]] of Kumamoto earthquakes occurs.\n\n==Births==\n*[[1126]] &ndash; [[Averroes]], Spanish physician and philosopher (d. 1198)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/10/day-1198-islamic-philosopher-averroes-dies-marrakech/|title=On this day in 1198: the Islamic philosopher Averro\u00ebs dies in Marrakech|date=10 December 2017|author=Dominic Selwood|website=The Telegraph|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[1204]] &ndash; [[Henry I of Castile|Henry I]], king of [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]] (d. 1217)<ref>{{cite book|author=E. Michael Gerli|title=Medieval Iberia: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=euVJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|date=4 December 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-77162-0|pages=299}}</ref>\n*[[1331]] &ndash; [[Jeanne-Marie de Maille]], French Roman Catholic saint (d. 1414)\n*[[1527]] &ndash; [[Abraham Ortelius]], Flemish cartographer and geographer (d. 1598)\n*[[1572]] &ndash; [[Adam Tanner (mathematician)|Adam Tanner]], Austrian mathematician, philosopher, and academic (d. 1632)\n*[[1578]] &ndash; [[Philip III of Spain]] (d. 1621)<ref>{{cite book|author=Herbert Norris|title=Tudor Costume and Fashion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yVdfZGj6NmkC&pg=PA677|date=1 January 1997|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-29845-0|pages=677}}</ref>\n*[[1629]] &ndash; [[Christiaan Huygens]], Dutch mathematician, astronomer, and physicist (d. 1695)<ref>{{cite book|author=John Gribbin|title=Q is for Quantum: An Encyclopedia of Particle Physics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zBsDkgI1uQsC&pg=PA181|date=22 February 2000|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-684-86315-3|pages=181}}</ref>\n*[[1668]] &ndash; [[Magnus Julius De la Gardie]], Swedish general and politician (d. 1741)\n*[[1678]] &ndash; [[Abraham Darby I]], English iron master (d. 1717)\n*[[1709]] &ndash; [[Charles Coll\u00e9]], French playwright and songwriter (d. 1783)\n*[[1714]] &ndash; [[Adam Gib]], Scottish minister and author (d. 1788)\n*[[1738]] &ndash; [[William Cavendish-Bentinck, 3rd Duke of Portland]], English politician, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1809)\n*[[1741]] &ndash; [[Emperor Momozono]] of Japan (d. 1762)\n*[[1769]] &ndash; [[Barth\u00e9lemy Catherine Joubert]], French general (d. 1799)\n*[[1773]] &ndash; [[Jean-Baptiste de Vill\u00e8le]], French politician, 6th [[Prime Minister of France]] (d. 1854)\n*[[1788]] &ndash; [[David G. Burnet]], American politician, 2nd [[President of the Republic of Texas|Vice-President of Texas]] (d. 1870)\n*[[1800]] &ndash; [[John Appold]], English engineer (d. 1865)\n*[[1812]] &ndash; [[George Grey]], Portuguese-New Zealand soldier, explorer, and politician, 11th [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] (d. 1898)\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[Dimitri Kipiani]], Georgian publicist and author (d. 1887)\n*[[1819]] &ndash; [[Harriett Ellen Grannis Arey]], American educator, author, editor, and publisher (d. 1901)<ref name=\"Herringshaw1904\">{{cite book|last=Herringshaw|first=Thomas William|title=Herringshaw's Encyclopedia of American Biography of the Nineteenth Century: Accurate and Succinct Biographies of Famous Men and Women in All Walks of Life who are Or Have Been the Acknowledged Leaders of Life and Thought of the United States Since Its Formation ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xxg7AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA50|edition=Public domain|year=1904|publisher=American Publishers' Association|pages=50\u2013}}</ref>\n*[[1827]] &ndash; [[Augustus Pitt Rivers]], English general, ethnologist, and archaeologist (d. 1900)\n*[[1852]] &ndash; [[Alexander Greenlaw Hamilton]], Australian biologist (d. 1941)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[Martin Lipp]], Estonian pastor and poet (d. 1923)\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Princess Beatrice of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1944)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Alfred Hoare Powell]], English architect, and designer and painter of pottery (d. 1960)\n*[[1866]] &ndash; [[Anne Sullivan]], American educator (d. 1936)\n*[[1868]] &ndash; [[Peter Behrens]], German architect, designed the [[AEG turbine factory]] (d. 1940)\n*[[1870]] &ndash; [[Victor Borisov-Musatov]], Russian painter and educator (d. 1905)\n*  1870   &ndash; [[Syd Gregory]], Australian cricketer and coach (d. 1929)\n*[[1872]] &ndash; [[Abdullah Yusuf Ali]], Indian-English scholar and translator (d. 1953)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Husain Salaahuddin]], Maldivian poet and scholar (d. 1948)\n*[[1882]] &ndash; [[Moritz Schlick]], German-Austrian physicist and philosopher (d. 1936)\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Ernst Robert Curtius]], German philologist and scholar (d. 1956)\n*  1886   &ndash; [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d T\u00f3th]], Hungarian poet and translator (d. 1928)\n*[[1889]] &ndash; [[Arnold J. Toynbee]], English historian and academic (d. 1975)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[B. R. Ambedkar]], Indian economist, jurist, and politician, 1st [[Minister of Law and Justice (India)|Indian Minister of Law and Justice]] (d. 1956)\n*  1891   &ndash; [[Otto Lasanen]], Finnish wrestler (d. 1958)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Juan Belmonte]], Spanish bullfighter (d. 1962)\n*  1892   &ndash; [[V. Gordon Childe]], Australian archaeologist and philologist (d. 1957)<ref>{{cite book|author=Sally Green|title=Prehistorian: A Biography of V. Gordon Childe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GeUZAAAAYAAJ|year=1981|publisher=Moonraker|page=1}}</ref>\n*  1892   &ndash; [[Claire Windsor]], American actress (d. 1972)\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[Sylvio Mantha]], Canadian ice hockey player, coach, and referee (d. 1974)\n*[[1903]] &ndash; [[Henry Corbin]], French philosopher and academic (d. 1978)\n*  1903   &ndash; [[Ruth Svedberg]], Swedish discus thrower and triathlete (d. 2002)\n*[[1904]] &ndash; [[John Gielgud]], English actor, director, and producer (d. 2000)<ref>{{cite book|author=Gyles Daubeney Brandreth|title=John Gielgud: a celebration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0itaAAAAMAAJ|year=1984|publisher=Pavilion|isbn=978-0-907516-38-5|page=12}}</ref>\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[Elizabeth Huckaby]], American author and educator (d. 1999)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Georg Lammers]], German sprinter (d. 1987)\n*  1905   &ndash; [[Jean Pierre-Bloch]], French author and activist (d. 1999)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Faisal of Saudi Arabia]], Saudi Arabian king (d. 1975)\n*[[1907]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Duvalier]], Haitian physician and politician, 40th [[President of Haiti]] (d. 1971)<ref>{{cite book|author=Frank J. Coppa|title=Encyclopedia of Modern Dictators: From Napoleon to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gTv99LBYSL4C&pg=PA84|year=2006|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-5010-0|pages=84}}</ref>\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[Robert Doisneau]], French photographer and journalist (d. 1994)\n*  1912   &ndash; [[Georg Siimenson]], Estonian footballer (d. 1978)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Jean Fournet]], French conductor (d. 2008)\n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Don Willesee]], Australian telegraphist and politician, 29th [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Australia)|Australian Minister for Foreign Affairs]] (d. 2003)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[Valerie Hobson]], English actress (d. 1998)\n*  1917   &ndash; [[Marvin Miller]], American baseball executive (d. 2012)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Mary Healy (entertainer)|Mary Healy]], American actress and singer (d. 2015)\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Shamshad Begum]], Pakistani-Indian singer (d. 2013)\n*  1919   &ndash; [[K. Saraswathi Amma]], Indian author and playwright (d. 1975)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Ivor Forbes Guest]], English lawyer, historian, and author (d. 2018)\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Thomas Schelling]], American economist and academic, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2016)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Audrey Long]], American actress (d. 2014)\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Roberto De Vicenzo]], Argentinian golfer (d. 2017)\n*[[1924]] &ndash; [[Shorty Rogers]], American trumpet player and composer (d. 1994)\n*  1924   &ndash; [[Joseph Ruskin]], American actor and producer (d. 2013)\n*  1924   &ndash; [[Mary Warnock, Baroness Warnock]], English philosopher, and academic (d. 2019)\n*[[1925]] &ndash; [[Abel Muzorewa]], Zimbabwean minister and politician, 1st [[Prime Minister of Zimbabwe Rhodesia]] (d. 2010)\n*  1925   &ndash; [[Rod Steiger]], American soldier and actor (d. 2002)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Barbara Anderson (writer)|Barbara Anderson]], New Zealand author (d. 2013)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Frank Daniel]], Czech director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 1996)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Gloria Jean]], American actress and singer (d. 2018)\n*  1926   &ndash; [[Liz Renay]], American actress and author (d. 2007)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[Alan MacDiarmid]], New Zealand chemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2007)\n*  1927   &ndash; [[Dany Robin]], French actress and singer (d. 1995)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Gerry Anderson]], English director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 2012)\n*  1929   &ndash; [[Inez Andrews]], African-American singer-songwriter (d. 2012)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[Martin Adolf Bormann]], German priest and theologian (d. 2013)\n*  1930   &ndash; [[Arnold Burns]], American lawyer and politician, 21st [[United States Deputy Attorney General]] (d. 2013)\n*  1930   &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 Desmaison]], French mountaineer (d. 2007)\n*  1930   &ndash; [[Bradford Dillman]], American actor and author (d. 2018)\n*[[1931]] &ndash; [[Geoffrey Dalton]], English admiral\n*  1931   &ndash; [[Paul Masnick]], Canadian ice hockey player\n*[[1932]] &ndash; [[Bill Bennett]], Canadian lawyer and politician, 27th [[Premier of British Columbia]] (d. 2015)\n*  1932   &ndash; [[Atef Ebeid]], Egyptian academic and politician, 47th [[List of Prime Ministers of Egypt|Prime Minister of Egypt]] (d. 2014)\n*  1932   &ndash; [[Loretta Lynn]], American singer-songwriter and musician \n*  1932   &ndash; [[Cameron Parker]], Scottish businessman and politician, [[Lord Lieutenant of Renfrewshire]]\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Paddy Hopkirk]], Northern Irish racing driver\n*  1933   &ndash; [[Boris Strugatsky]], Russian author (d. 2012)\n*  1933   &ndash; [[Yuri Oganessian]], Armenian-Russian nuclear physicist\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Fredric Jameson]], American philosopher and theorist\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Susan Cunliffe-Lister, Baroness Masham of Ilton]], English table tennis player, swimmer, and politician<ref>{{Cite book|title=Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage|date=2003|publisher=Burke's Peerage|isbn=9780971196629|editor-last=Mosley|editor-first=Charles|doi = 10.5118/bpbk.2003}}</ref>\n*  1935   &ndash; [[John Oliver (bishop)|John Oliver]], English bishop\n*  1935   &ndash; [[Erich von D\u00e4niken]], Swiss historian and author\n*[[1936]] &ndash; [[Arlene Martel]], American actress and singer (d. 2014)\n*  1936   &ndash; [[Bobby Nichols]], American golfer\n*  1936   &ndash; [[Frank Serpico]], American-Italian soldier, police officer and lecturer\n*[[1937]] &ndash; [[Efi Arazi]], Israeli businessman, founded the [[Scailex Corporation]] (d. 2013)\n*  1937   &ndash; [[Sepp Mayerl]], Austrian mountaineer (d. 2012)\n*[[1938]] &ndash; [[Mahmud Esad Co\u015fan]], Turkish author and academic (d. 2001)\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[Julie Christie]], English actress and activist\n*  1940   &ndash; [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Thornes]], English archbishop and academic\n*  1940   &ndash; [[Richard Thompson (physician)|Richard Thompson]], English physician and academic\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Pete Rose]], American baseball player and manager\n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[Valeriy Brumel]], Soviet high jumper (d. 2003)\n*  1942   &ndash; [[Valentin Lebedev]], Russian engineer and astronaut\n*  1942   &ndash; [[Bj\u00f6rn Rosengren]], Swedish po