rican baseball player (b. 1911)\n*[[1969]] &ndash; [[Matilde Mu\u00f1oz Sampedro]], Spanish actress (b. 1900)\n*[[1975]] &ndash; [[G\u00fcnter Dyhrenfurth]], German-Swiss mountaineer, geologist, and explorer (b. 1886)\n*  1975   &ndash; [[Fredric March]], American actor (b. 1897)\n*[[1976]] &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 Revueltas]], Mexican author and activist (b. 1914)\n*[[1978]] &ndash; [[Joe Gordon]], American baseball player and manager (b. 1915)\n*  1978   &ndash; [[F. R. Leavis]], English educator and critic (b. 1895)\n*[[1983]] &ndash; [[Pete Farndon]], English bassist ([[The Pretenders]]) (b. 1952)\n*  1983   &ndash; [[Gianni Rodari]], Italian journalist and author (b. 1920)\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Simone de Beauvoir]], French novelist and philosopher (b. 1908)\n*[[1990]] &ndash; [[Thurston Harris]], American singer (b. 1931)\n*  1990   &ndash; [[Olabisi Onabanjo]], Nigerian politician, 3rd [[Governor of Ogun State]] (b. 1927)\n*[[1992]] &ndash; [[Irene Greenwood]], Australian radio broadcaster and feminist and peace activist (b. 1898)<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fisher |first1=Catherine Horne |title=Greenwood, Irene Adelaide (1898\u20131992) |url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/greenwood-irene-adelaide-25528 |website=Australian Dictionary of Biography |publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University |accessdate=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Salimuzzaman Siddiqui]], Pakistani chemist and scholar (b. 1897)\n*[[1995]] &ndash; [[Burl Ives]], American actor, folk singer, and writer (b. 1909)\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Ellen Corby]], American actress and screenwriter (b. 1911)\n*  1999   &ndash; [[Anthony Newley]], English singer-songwriter and actor (b. 1931)\n*  1999   &ndash; [[Bill Wendell]], American television announcer (b. 1924)\n*[[2000]] &ndash; [[Phil Katz]], American computer programmer, co-created the [[zip (file format)|zip file format]] (b. 1962)\n*  2000   &ndash; [[August R. Lindt]], Swiss lawyer and politician (b. 1905)\n*  2000   &ndash; [[Wilf Mannion]], English footballer (b. 1918)\n*[[2001]] &ndash; [[Jim Baxter]], Scottish footballer (b. 1939)\n*  2001   &ndash; [[Hiroshi Teshigahara]], Japanese director, producer, and screenwriter (b. 1927)\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[Jyrki Otila]], Finnish politician (b. 1941)\n*[[2004]] &ndash; [[Micheline Charest]], English-Canadian television producer, co-founded the [[Cookie Jar Group]] (b. 1953)\n*[[2006]] &ndash; [[Mahmut Bakalli]], Kosovo politician (b. 1936)\n*[[2007]] &ndash; [[June Callwood]], Canadian journalist, author, and activist (b. 1924)\n*  2007   &ndash; [[Don Ho]], American singer and ukulele player (b. 1930)\n*  2007   &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 R\u00e9mond]], French historian and economist (b. 1918)\n*[[2008]] &ndash; [[Tommy Holmes]], American baseball player and manager (b. 1917)\n*  2008   &ndash; [[Ollie Johnston]], American animator and voice actor (b. 1912)\n*[[2009]] &ndash; [[Maurice Druon]], French author (b. 1918)\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Israr Ahmed]], Pakistani theologian and scholar (b. 1932)\n*  2010   &ndash; [[Alice Miller (psychologist)|Alice Miller]], Polish-French psychologist and author (b. 1923)\n*  2010   &ndash; [[Peter Steele]], American singer-songwriter and bass player (b. 1962)\n*[[2011]] &ndash; [[Jean Gratton]], Canadian Roman Catholic bishop (b. 1924)\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[\u00c9mile Bouchard]], Canadian ice hockey player and coach (b. 1919)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Jonathan Frid]], Canadian actor (b. 1924)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Piermario Morosini]], Italian footballer (b. 1986)\n*[[2013]] &ndash; [[Efi Arazi]], Israeli businessman, founded the [[Scailex Corporation]] (b. 1937)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Colin Davis]], English conductor and educator (b. 1927)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[R. P. Goenka]], Indian businessman, founded [[RPG Group]] (b. 1930)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[George Jackson (songwriter)|George Jackson]], American singer-songwriter (b. 1945)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Armando Villanueva]], Peruvian politician, 121st [[Prime Minister of Peru]] (b. 1915)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Charlie Wilson (Ohio politician)|Charlie Wilson]], American politician (b. 1943)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Nina Cassian]], Romanian poet and critic (b. 1924)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Crad Kilodney]], American-Canadian author (b. 1948)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Wally Olins]], English businessman and academic (b. 1930)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Mick Staton]], American soldier and politician (b. 1940)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Klaus Bednarz]], German journalist and author (b. 1942)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Mark Reeds]], Canadian-American ice hockey player and coach (b. 1960)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Percy Sledge]], American singer (b. 1940)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Roberto Tucci]], Italian cardinal and theologian (b. 1921)\n*[[2019]] &ndash; [[Bibi Andersson]], Swedish actress (b.1935) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/apr/15/bibi-andersson-obituary|title=Bibi Andersson obituary|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n*[[Ambedkar Jayanti]] (India)\n*[[Black Day (South Korea)]]\n*Christian [[Calendar of saints|feast day]]:\n**[[Anthony, John, and Eustathius]]\n**[[B\u00e9n\u00e9zet]]\n**[[Henry Beard Delany]] ([[Episcopal Church (USA)]])\n**[[Domnina of Terni]]\n**[[Lidwina]]\n**[[Peter Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n**[[Tiburtius, Valerian, and Maximus]]\n**[[April 14 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n*[[Public holidays in Iraq|Commemoration of Anfal Genocide Against the Kurds]] ([[Iraqi Kurdistan]]) \n*[[Day of Mologa]] ([[Yaroslavl Oblast]], Russia)\n*[[Day of the Georgian language]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]])\n*[[Maldivian language#Dhivehi Language Day|Dhivehi Language Day]] ([[Maldives]])\n*[[N'Ko Alphabet Day]] ([[Mande languages|Mande speakers]])\n*[[Pan American Day]] (several countries in [[The Americas]])\n*[[South and Southeast Asian New Year]], celebrated on the [[sidereal year|sidereal]] [[Vernal equinox (Northern Hemisphere)|vernal equinox]]. (see [[April 13]]):\n**[[Culture of Assam|Assamese]] New Year, or [[Bohag Bihu]] ([[India|India's]] [[Assam Valley]])\n**[[Bengali culture|Bengali]] New Year, or [[Pohela Boishakh]] ([[Bangladesh]] and [[India|India's]] [[West Bengal]] state)\n**[[Burmese culture|Burmese]] New Year, or [[Thingyan]] ([[Myanmar]])\n**[[Hindu]] and [[Sikh]] New Year, or [[Vaisakhi]] ([[Punjab region]])\n**[[Khmer people|Khmer]] New Year, or [[Cambodian New Year|Chol Chnam Thmey]] ([[Cambodia]])\n**[[Lao New Year]], or Pi Mai Lao ([[Laos]])\n**[[Mahl people|Mahl]] New Year, or Alathu Aharudhuvas ([[Maldives]] and [[India|India's]] [[Lakshadweep]] and [[Kerala]] state)\n**[[Maithil]]i New Year, or [[Maithili New Year|Jude Sheetal]] ([[Mithila (ancient)|Mithila region]]) \n**[[Malayali people|Malayali]] New Year, or [[Vishu]] ([[India|India's]] [[Kerala]] state)\n**[[Nepali people|Nepali]] New Year, or [[Vikram Samvat|Navabarsha]] / Vaishak Ek ([[Nepal]])\n**[[Oriya people|Oriya/Odia]] New Year, or [[Pana Sankranti]] ([[India|India's]] [[Odisha]] state)\n**[[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] New Year, or [[Sinhala new year|Aluth Avurudhu]] ([[Sri Lanka]])\n**[[Tamil people|Tamil]] New Year, or [[Puthandu]] ([[India|India's]] [[Tamil Nadu]] state)\n**[[Thai culture|Thai]] New Year, or [[Songkran]], celebrated from [[13 April|13]] to 15 April ([[Thailand]])\n**[[Tuluva]] New Year, or [[Bisu (festival)|Bisu]] ([[India|India's]] [[Karnataka]] state)\n*The first day of [[Takayama Festival|Takayama Spring Festival]] ([[Takayama, Gifu]], Japan)\n*[[Youth Day (Angola)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/14 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=04|day=14}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/April_14 Today in Canadian History]\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:April]]\n", "name_user": "Stevehem", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEvents", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/April_14"}
{"title_page": "Michael John LaChiusa", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Michael John LaChiusa\n| image       = Michael John LaChiusa Headshot.jpg\n| caption     = Official publicity photo\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age |1962|07|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Chautauqua, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Composer, lyricist, librettist\n| genre       =\n| movement    =\n| period      = 1989\u2014present\n| signature   = \n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n}}\n'''Michael John LaChiusa''' (born July 24, 1962) is an [[United States|American]] [[musical theatre]] and [[opera]] [[composer]], [[lyricist]], and [[libretto|librettist]]. He is best known for musically esoteric shows such as ''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'', ''[[Marie Christine]]'', ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]'', and ''[[See What I Wanna See]]''.<ref name=\"feud\"/><ref name=\"post\"/> He was nominated for four [[Tony Award]]s in 2000 for his score and book for both ''Marie Christine'' and ''The Wild Party'' and received another nomination in 1996 for his work on the libretto for ''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold (musical)|Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]''.\n\n==Biography==\nLaChiusa grew up in [[Chautauqua, New York]], the eldest of three boys in an [[Italians|Italian]] [[Catholic]] family.  His parents had a \"[v]ery mentally abusive\" relationship; Michael was not close to his father, but was encouraged by his mother to pursue his interest in music.<ref name=\"somany\">Green, Jesse.  [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/05/theater/newsandfeatures/05gree.html?_r=1&scp=2&sq=%22so+many+musicals+to+write%22&st=nyt&oref=slogin \"So Many Musicals to Write, So Little Time\"], [[The New York Times]], 2006-03-05.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  He taught himself to play piano at the age of seven and had little formal music training.  LaChiusa was influenced early on by the music of \"modern American composers\" such as [[John Corigliano]], [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]], and [[Philip Glass]], as well as the [[musical theatre]] composers [[George Gershwin]], [[Richard Rodgers]], and [[Stephen Sondheim]].<ref name=\"opera\">Blue, Robert Wilder.  [http://www.usoperaweb.com/2001/july/lachiusa1.htm \"Lovers and Friends\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20030116070551/http://www.usoperaweb.com/2001/july/lachiusa1.htm |date=2003-01-16 }}, USOperaWeb, June 2001.  Retrieved on 2008-03-01.</ref><ref>Heilpern, John.  [http://www.observer.com/node/47170 \"Worried About the War? Why Not Forget Your Troubles at Little Fish\"], [[The New York Observer]], 2003-03-03.  Retrieved on 2008-03-01.</ref>  LaChiusa graduated high school early and enrolled in a television journalism program, but he dropped out after a semester.<ref name=\"somany\"/><ref name=\"opera\"/>\n\nIn 1980, LaChiusa moved to New York City, where he took jobs as a music director and accompanist while trying to find songwriting work.  In the mid-1980s, he joined the [[BMI Lehman Engel Musical Theater Workshop]], where he was strongly influenced by a series of mentors and where he segued from writing \"camp\" songs to more serious work.<ref name=\"post\">Pressley, Nelson.  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A9384-2004Oct29.html \"At Long Last, All Systems Are Gogh For 'Yellow': Composer LaChiusa's Difficult Musical Shapes Up\"], [[The Washington Post]], 2004-10-31.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  In 1993, [[The Public Theater]]'s producer [[George C. Wolfe]] presented LaChiusa's ''[[First Lady Suite]]''.  A year later, [[Lincoln Center]] produced his musical ''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'' [[Off Broadway]].  A series of interconnected stories about love based on [[Arthur Schnitzler]]'s play ''[[La Ronde (play)|La Ronde]]'', ''Hello Again'' was nominated for ten [[Drama Desk Award]]s, including three (Outstanding Book of a Musical, Outstanding Music, and Outstanding Lyrics) for LaChiusa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dramadesk.com/1993_1994dd.htm |title=Drama Desk Awards 2006 - Winners 2001 |publisher=Dramadesk.com |accessdate=2013-12-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20060424094843/http://dramadesk.com/1993_1994dd.htm |archivedate=2006-04-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, LaChiusa wrote additional book material for the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold (musical)|Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]'' (an adaptation of [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]'s [[Chronicle of a Death Foretold|1981 novella of the same name]].)  For the book, written with [[Graciela Daniele]] and [[Jim Lewis (librettist)|Jim Lewis]], LaChiusa received a [[Tony Award]] nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book of a Musical]].\n\nDuring the 1999-2000 season, two of LaChiusa's large-scale musicals premiered on Broadway: ''[[Marie Christine]]'' and ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]''.  ''Marie Christine'', a retelling of the [[Medea]] myth set in 19th-century [[Louisiana]], starred [[Audra McDonald]] and attracted controversy due to its grim subject matter and demanding score\u2014''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that \"even the formidable and classically trained McDonald could sing it only six times a week, rather than the standard eight.\"<ref name=\"somany\"/>  ''Marie Christine'' closed after 42 performances; LaChiusa later said that the show \"in my mind should have been performed for three performances....  Only three.  It's huge, and it's intensely difficult\".<ref name=\"post\"/>  ''The Wild Party'' was based on the [[The Wild Party (poem)|1928 poem of the same name]] by [[Joseph Moncure March]] and starred [[Toni Collette]], [[Mandy Patinkin]], and [[Eartha Kitt]].  ''The Wild Party'' struggled commercially; after receiving seven Tony nominations but failing to win a single one, producers closed the show.<ref>McKinley, Jesse.  [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9400E7D9143FF934A35755C0A9669C8B63&scp=1&sq=%22the+wild+party%22+AND+%22tony%22+AND+%22miracle%22&st=nyt \"Shut Out of Tonys, ''The Wild Party'' Is Over\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 2000-06-07.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  For both ''Marie Christine'' and ''The Wild Party'', LaChiusa received Tony nominations for Best Book of a Musical and [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Little Fish (musical)|Little Fish]]'', an uncharacteristically cheerful one-act musical for LaChiusa, based on two short stories by [[Deborah Eisenberg]], premiered Off-Broadway.  The show's failure sent LaChiusa into a funk; he recalled, \"I went, 'My God, they don't want the hard stuff and more challenging material here in this city from me.  They don't want something nice and fun, either.  What am I supposed to do?'\"<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\nIn August 2005, LaChiusa published an article in ''[[Opera News]]'' that disparaged several successful, upbeat Broadway musicals of the 2000s, among them ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' and ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', which LaChiusa dubbed a \"faux-musical\".<ref name=\"feud\">[[Simonson, Robert]].  [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/11/theater/newsandfeatures/11spat.html \"2 Broadway Composers Do Inharmonious Battle\"], ''The New York Times'', 2005-08-11.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  He continued, \"Instead of choreography, there is dancing. Instead of crafted songwriting, there is tune-positioning. Faux-musicals are mechanical; they have to be. For expectations to be met, there can be no room for risk, derring-do or innovation.\"<ref name=\"feud\"/>  The article caused a great deal of controversy and provoked shocked responses from several of LaChiusa's colleagues, who saw it as an attack.<ref name=\"feud\"/>\n\nIn October 2005, LaChiusa's musical ''[[See What I Wanna See]]'', based on the stories \"In a Grove,\" \"The Dragon,\" and \"Kesa and Morito\" by [[Ry\u016bnosuke Akutagawa]], opened Off-Broadway at the Public Theater and closed on December 4, 2005.<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=4459 ''See What I Wanna See''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111054906/http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=4459 |date=2010-01-11 }} Internet Off-Broadway listing, accessed September 28, 2015</ref><ref name=\"somany\"/>  LaChiusa was nominated for Drama Desk Awards for Outstanding Music and Outstanding Lyrics.\n\nIn September 2008, he was quoted in ''[[Opera News]] Online'' as working on an adaptation of [[Bizet]]'s opera ''[[Carmen]]'' with [[Tony Award|Tony]] winner [[Audra McDonald]] in mind.<ref>Portantiere, Michael. [http://www.metoperafamily.org/operanews/issue/article.aspx?id=4980&issueID=325 \"Over the Borderline\"], [http://www.metoperafamily.org/operanews Opera News Online], September 2008, vol 73, no. 3. Retrieved on 2008-09-02.</ref> <!-- Did these happen?  If not, I suggest deleting the paragarph -->\n\nIn April 2009, the [[Signature Theatre (Arlington VA)|Signature Theatre]], [[Arlington, Virginia]], premiered ''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]'', a musical adaptation of [[Edna Ferber]]'s [[Giant (novel)|1952 novel of the same name]] with music and lyrics by LaChiusa and book by [[Sybille Pearson]], who wrote the book for the 1983 musical ''[[Baby (musical)|Baby]]''.<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/115609.html \"DC's Signature Theatre Will Premiere LaChiusa Musical Giant in 2009; Ace and Whistle Also on Schedule\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308134147/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/115609.html |date=2008-03-08 }}, [[Playbill]], 2008-03-04.  Retrieved on 2008-03-04.</ref>\n\n''[[Queen of the Mist]]'' is a musical adaption of the story of [[Annie Edson Taylor]], the first person to survive going over Niagara Falls in a barrel. Commissioned by Off-Broadway theatre company the [[Transport Group]] ''Queen of the Mist'' received a developmental lab in fall 2010, and opened in November 2011 at The Gym at Judson. With direction by Jack Cummings III and choreography by Scott Rink, the musical stars [[Mary Testa]] and [[Julia Murney]].<ref>Brantley, Ben.[http://theater.nytimes.com/2011/11/07/theater/reviews/queen-of-the-mist-at-the-gym-at-judson-review.html \"Theater Review:Obsessed With Taking the Plunge\"] ''The New York Times'', November 6, 2011</ref>\n\nLaChiusa's work, ''Nine Fathers of Ariel'', is \"a dance musical which centers on a mother's effort to provide her son with good fathering in the face of a war-obsessed world\".<ref name=nine/> It had a 29-hour private industry reading on April 5, 2014. It was a co-collaboration with Ellen Fitzhugh, with [[Graciela Daniele]] directing and musical direction by Mary Mitchell Campbell. The cast included [[Tonya Pinkins]], [[Marc Kudisch]], [[Malcolm Gets]], [[Telly Leung]], Bryce Ryness, [[Darius de Haas]], [[Stanley Bahorek]], Sydney James Harcourt, Ashley Robinson, Casey Robinson, and Hayley Feinstein.<ref name=nine>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/189570-Reading-of-Michael-John-LaChiusa-Ellen-Fitzhugh-Dance-Musical-to-Feature-Tonya-Pinkins-Marc-Kudisch-Malcolm-Gets-Telly-Leung-and-More \"Reading of Michael John LaChiusa Ellen Fitzhugh Dance Musical to Feature Tonya Pinkins Marc Kudisch Malcolm Gets Telly Leung and More\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407075958/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/189570-Reading-of-Michael-John-LaChiusa-Ellen-Fitzhugh-Dance-Musical-to-Feature-Tonya-Pinkins-Marc-Kudisch-Malcolm-Gets-Telly-Leung-and-More |date=2014-04-07 }} Playbill, April 2, 2014</ref>\n\nLaChiusa's musical ''[[First Daughter Suite]]'' premiered Off-Broadway at the Public Theater on October 6, 2015 (previews), and was directed by Kirsten Sanderson. He stated about the work: \"While he didn't want to fully imitate ''First Lady Suite'', LaChiusa felt that the new piece could be an extension of the earlier piece. It would not, however, be a sequel.\" The musical looks at the women in the lives of Presidents [[Richard Nixon]], [[Jimmy Carter]], [[Ronald Reagan]], [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[George W. Bush]].<ref>Fox, Jenna Tesse. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/why-michael-john-lachiusa-is-obsessed-with-exploring-unheard-stories-of-women-especially-in-the-white-house-364099# \"Why Michael John LaChiusa is \"Obsessed\" With Exploring Unheard Stories of Women \u2014 Especially in the White House\"] Playbill, September 28, 2015</ref> The women are: Patricia Nixon, played by [[Barbara Walsh]] and daughters Tricia played by Betsy Morgan and Julie played by Cassie Levy; Rosalynn Carter, played by Rachel Bay Jones and Amy Carter played by Carly Tamer; Betty Ford played by [[Alison Fraser]] and Susan Ford played by Betsy Morgan; Patti Davis played by Cassie Levy and mother Nancy Reagan, played by Alison Fraser; and Barbara Bush played by [[Mary Testa]] and daughter-in-law Laura played by Rachel Bay Jones.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/alison-fraser-rachel-bay-jones-caissie-levy-barbara-walsh-star-in-first-daughter-suite-beginning-tonight-365704# \"Alison Fraser, Rachel Bay Jones, Caissie Levy, Barbara Walsh Star in 'First Daughter Suite', Beginning Tonight\"] Playbill, October 6, 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.publictheater.org/Global/Press/2015/FirstDaughter_CompleteCasting.pdf \"'First Daughter Suite' Listing, Press Release\"] publictheater.org, accessed September 28, 2015</ref>\n\nThe world premiere of LaChiusa's musical ''Rain'' (book by [[Sybille Pearson]], based on the short story \"Rain\" by [[Somerset Maugham]]),  runs March 24-May 1, 2016 at San Diego's [[Old Globe Theatre]]. It is directed by [[Barry Edelstein]], and stars [[Eden Espinosa]] as Sadie Thompson.<ref name=globe>{{cite web|title=Rain |url=http://theoldglobe.org/tickets/production.aspx?PID=11875 |website=The Old Globe Theatre |accessdate=18 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315082450/http://theoldglobe.org/tickets/production.aspx?PID=11875 |archivedate=15 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>Viagas, Robert. [http://www.playbill.com/article/full-cast-announced-for-new-michael-john-lachiusa-musical-rain-com-384950# \"Full Cast Announced for New Michael John LaChiusa Musical 'Rain'\"] Playbill, February 2016</ref><ref>Viagas, Robert. [http://www.playbill.com/article/eden-espinosa-stars-in-today-39-s-world-premiere-of-michael-john-lachiusa-39-s-musical-rain-com-384950# \"Eden Espinosa Stars in Today's World Premiere of Michael John LaChiusa's Musical 'Rain'\"] Playbill, April 1, 2016</ref>\n\n===Teaching===\n[[File:MJLC Columbia College Master Class Photo.jpg|thumb|Michael John LaChiusa speaks to students after a performance of his musical [[Bernarda Alba (musical)]] at Columbia College.]]\nLaChiusa is an adjunct professor at the Graduate Musical Theatre Writing Program at the [[Tisch School of the Arts]] at [[New York University]].\n\n===Performing===\nLaChiusa also performs at various cabaret and concert venues, including:\n*''La La Chiusa'' at [[Joe's Pub]] (October 16, 2000 \u2013 November 5, 2000);<ref>[http://www.theatermania.com/new-york/shows/la-la-lachiusa_6453/ La La LaChiusa listing at Joes Pub, October-November 2000] theatermania.com, accessed July 27, 2009</ref>\n*''The Girly Show'', as part of [[Lincoln Center]]'s American Songbook Series (May 17, 2004)<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/Photo_Coverage_The_Girly_Show_a_Celebration_of_the_Music_of_Michael_John_La_Chiusa_20040519 \"Photo Coverage: 'The Girly Show' a Celebration of the Music of Michael John La Chiusa,\"] broadwayworld.com, May 19, 2004</ref> and at Cinespace, Hollywood (August 15, 2005);<ref>BWW News Desk. [http://broadwayworld.com/article/LaChiusa_Appears_at_Blanks_Gala_for_Girly_Show_Aug_15_20050809 \"LaChiusa Appears at Blank's Gala for Girly Show, Aug. 15,\"] broadwayworld.com, August 9, 2005</ref>\n*''Platform Series'' at [[Lincoln Center Theater]] (March 29, 2006);<ref>BWW News Desk. [http://broadwayworld.com/article/LaChiusa_Appears_at_LCT_as_Part_of_Platform_Series_March_29_20060329 \"LaChiusa Appears at LCT as Part of Platform Series, March 29,\"] broadwayworld.com, March 29, 2006;</ref>\n*''Little Fish in Concert'' at Joe's Pub (July 10, 2006);<ref>[http://www.theatermania.com/new-york/shows/little-fish_122785/ ''Little Fish'' in concert listing for July 10, 2006] theatermania.com, accessed July 27, 2009</ref>\n*Concert that featured music from ''Bernarda Alba'' and other LaChiusa scores as well as a ''Little Fish'' CD Release party ; Alice Ripley and Lea DeLaria, appeared at Joe's Pub (September 8, 2008);<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/120114-LaChiusa_to_Celebrate_Little_Fish_CD_with_Joe's_Pub_Concert LaChiusa to Celebrate Little Fish CD with Joe's Pub Concert,\"] playbill.com, August 5, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joespub.com/component/option,com_shows/task,view/Itemid,40/id,4085 |title=Michael John LaChiusa:Little Fish release concert listing for September 8, 2008 |publisher=Joespub.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>[http://shkbuzz.wordpress.com/2008/09/18/photo-moments-little-fish-at-joes-pub/  \"Photo Moments; Little Fish at Joe's Pub\"] shkbuzz.wordpress.com, September 18, 2008</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nIn 2004, LaChiusa told ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that he was a \"gay man, happily single\".<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\n==Work==\n\n===Broadway productions===\n*''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold (musical)|Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]'' (additional book and lyrics with [[Graciela Daniele]] and Jim Lewis; music by [[Bob Telson]]) (1995)\n*''[[Marie Christine]]'' (1999)\n*''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]'' (book with [[George C. Wolfe]]) (2000)\n\n===Off-Broadway productions===\n*''[[First Lady Suite]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'' (1994)\n*''The Petrified Prince'' (book by Edward Gallardo) (1994)\n*''[[Little Fish (musical)|Little Fish]]'' (2003)\n*''[[See What I Wanna See]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Bernarda Alba (musical)|Bernarda Alba]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Queen of the Mist]]'' (2011)<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=5832 ''Queen of the Mist'' listing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525143949/http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=5832 |date=2015-05-25 }} Internet Off-Broadway Database listing, accessed November 8, 2011</ref>\n*''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]'' (2012)\n*''[[First daughter suite|First Daughter Suite]]'' (2015)<ref>[http://www.publictheater.org/en/Public-Theater-Season/2015-2016-Season \"Public Theater 2015-2016 Season\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626185927/http://www.publictheater.org/en/Public-Theater-Season/2015-2016-Season/ |date=2015-06-26 }} public theater.org, accessed June 25, 2015</ref>\n\n===Other theatre===\n*''Bittersweet'', book, music and lyrics by Jerry Young; Boston, MA. Musical Director Michael Lachiusa. (1979)\n*''Buzzsaw Berkeley'', book by [[Doug Wright]], music and lyrics by LaChiusa; WPA Theater, New York City (1989)\n*''[[Broken Sleep]]'' book by [[Donald Margulies]], Williamstown Theatre Festival, Williamstown, MA, 3 plays with music (1997)<ref>Sommer, Elyse.[http://www.curtainup.com/brokensl.html \"CurtainUp Reviews Broken Sleep: Three Plays\"] curtainup.com, accessed July 27, 2009</ref>\n*''The Nutcracker'', new musical theatre version (translated into Japanese) of ''The Nutcracker'', book by [[Amon Miyamoto]], music and lyrics by LaChiusa; premiere in Tokyo (2001)<ref>LaChiusa, Michael.[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/07/theater/theater-making-sugar-plum-fairies-sing-sweetly-in-japanese.html?pagewanted=all  \"Theatre; Making Sugar Plum Fairies Sing, Sweetly, in Japanese,\"]''The New York Times'', July 7, 2002</ref>\n*''[[The Highest Yellow]]'', music and lyrics by LaChiusa, book by John Strand; musical commissioned and premiered by [[Signature Theatre (Arlington, Virginia)|Signature Theatre]] [[Arlington, Virginia]] (2004)<ref>Toscano, Michael.[http://www.theatermania.com/virginia/reviews/11-2004/the-highest-yellow_5321.html \"Review:''The Highest Yellow''\"], theatermania.com, November 9, 2004</ref>\n*''[[Hotel C'est L'Amour]]'', musical with music and lyrics by LaChiusa and conceived by Daniel Henning; premiere at The Blank Theatre Company, Los Angeles, California (2006)<ref>Hernandez, Ernio. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/102444-LaChiusa_Work_Hotel_C'est_L'Amour_with_Vicki_Lewis_Opens_in_L.A. \"LaChiusa Work Hotel C'est L'Amour with Vicki Lewis Opens in L.A.,\"] playbill.com, September 30, 2006</ref>\n*''[[Inner Voices: Solo Musicals]]'', three musicals in one act: Act 1 is ''Tres Ninas'', lyrics and music by Ellen Fitzhugh and LaChiusa; Zipper Theater, New York City (2008)<ref>Isherwood, Charles. [http://theater2.nytimes.com/2008/05/23/theater/reviews/23voic.html?partner=rssnyt&emc=rss \"Woman Troubles, in a Handy Musical Variety Pack\",] ''The New York Times'', May 23, 2008</ref>\n*''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]'', music and lyrics by LaChiusa, book by [[Sybille Pearson]], Signature Theatre, Arlington, Virginia (2009)\n*''Los Otros'', book and lyrics by Ellen Fitzhugh, music by LaChiusa, directed by [[Graciela Daniele]], commissioned by Center Theatre Group; [[Mark Taper Forum]], Los Angeles, California (2012)<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/166238-Michele-Pawk-and-Julio-Monge-Sing-Los-Otros-a-New-Musical-by-Michael-John-LaChiusa-and-Ellen-Fitzhugh \"Michele Pawk and Julio Monge Sing 'Los Otros', a New Musical by Michael John LaChiusa and Ellen Fitzhugh\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524194007/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/166238-Michele-Pawk-and-Julio-Monge-Sing-Los-Otros-a-New-Musical-by-Michael-John-LaChiusa-and-Ellen-Fitzhugh |date=2012-05-24 }} playbill.com, May 23, 2012</ref>\n*''Rain,'' book by [[Sybille Pearson]], music and lyrics by LaChiusa, directed by [[Barry Edelstein]], [[The Old Globe Theatre]], San Diego, California (2016)<ref name=globe/>\n\n===Opera, song cycles and other music===\n*''Four Short Operas: Break, Agnes, Eulogy For Mr. Hamm, Lucky Nurse'', book, music and lyrics by LaChiusa, [[Playwrights Horizons]] (14 performances) (1991)\n*''Desert of Roses'', libretto by LaChiusa, music by [[Robert Moran]], an opera commissioned and premiered by [[Houston Grand Opera]] (1992)<ref>[http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/desert_of_roses.htm \"''Desert of Roses'' information\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704170452/http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/desert_of_roses.htm |date=2008-07-04 }} members.macconnect.com</ref>\n*''[[From the Towers of the Moon]]'', libretto by LaChiusa, music by Robert Moran, an opera commissioned and premiered by [[Minnesota Opera]] (1992)<ref>[http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/from_the_towers_of_the_moon.htm \"''From the Towers of the Moon'' information\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011162847/http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/from_the_towers_of_the_moon.htm |date=2008-10-11 }}, members.macconnect.com</ref>\n*''Tania'', libretto by LaChiusa, music by [[Anthony Davis (composer)|Anthony Davis]], Plays and Players Theater, New York City, and recorded (1992)<ref>Rothstein, Edward. [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/19/arts/review-opera-tania-cinque-and-the-super-bowl.html?pagewanted=all \"Review/Opera; Tania, Cinque and the Super Bowl,\"] ''The New York Times'', June 19, 1992</ref>\n*''Lovers and Friends (Chautauqua Variations)'', commissioned and performed by [[Lyric Opera of Chicago]], book, music and lyrics by LaChiusa (2001)<ref>Waleson, Heidi. [http://www.andante.com/article/article.cfm?id=13687&highlight=1&highlightterms=&lstKeywords= \"Chilly Scenes of Winter,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040228032852/http://www.andante.com/article/article.cfm?id=13687&highlight=1&highlightterms=&lstKeywords= |date=2004-02-28 }} andante.com, July 2001.</ref>\n*''The Seven Deadly Sins: A Song Cycle'', \"The Christian Thing to Do\", contribution to song cycle commissioned for [[Audra McDonald]], performed at [[Carnegie Hall]], New York City (2004)<!--an article on this work was deleted as a stub--><ref>Gans, Andrew.[https://archive.is/20130104150401/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/86517-Audra_McDonald_Premieres_The_Seven_Deadly_Sins_June_2_at_Zankel_Hall  \"Audra McDonald Premieres The Seven Deadly Sins June 2 at Zankel Hall\"], playbill.com, June 2, 2004</ref>\n*''The Cello Project'', chamber work for cello, part of a song cycle for Peter Sachon, cellist, premiered at the Leonard Nimoy Thalia at [[Symphony Space]], New York City (2005)<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/91560-LaChiusa_Schwartz_Bucchino_Marzullo_and_More_Write_Cello_Pieces_for_March_7_Concert \"LaChiusa, Schwartz, Bucchino, Marzullo and More Write Cello Pieces for March 7 Concert,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629231753/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/91560-LaChiusa_Schwartz_Bucchino_Marzullo_and_More_Write_Cello_Pieces_for_March_7_Concert |date=2009-06-29 }} playbill.com, March 7, 2005</ref>\n*''pre.view'', choreography by [[Taye Diggs]] and Andrew Palermo, music by LaChiusa, Ailey Citigroup Theater, New York City (2006)<ref>Hernandez, Ernio. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/97673-Broadway%27s_Diggs_and_Palermo_Create_Dance_Play_pre.view_with_LaChiusa_Music \"Broadway's Diggs and Palermo Create Dance Play pre.view with LaChiusa Music,\"] playbill.com, January 31, 2006</ref>\n*''Send (who are you? i love you)'' music and libretto by LaChiusa, co-conceived by LaChiusa and Lonny Price for [[Audra McDonald]], performed by McDonald with Houston Grand Opera (2006)<ref>Gans, Andrew.  [https://archive.is/20120908085048/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/98256-Audra_McDonald_Makes_Houston_Grand_Opera_Debut_March_4 \"Audra McDonald Makes Houston Grand Opera Debut March 4,\"] playbill.com, March 4, 2006</ref>\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Wonder Pets]]'': LaChiusa wrote music for 15 episodes of this animated series (2006\u201307)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0775407/fullcredits Internet Movie Database listing for ''Wonder Pets'', credits] imdb.com</ref>\n*''Broadway: The Golden Age'': LaChiusa was one of many Broadway insiders interviewed for this documentary (2003)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0303797/ \"Broadway: The Golden Age\" listing] imdb.com</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Association\n!Category\n!Title\n!Result\n|-\n|1994\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Lyrics|Outstanding Lyrics]]\n|''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Book of a Musical|Outstanding Book]]\n|''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|1996\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book]]\n|''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2000\n||[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book]]\n|''[[Marie Christine]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book]]\n|''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Score|Best Score]]\n|''[[Marie Christine]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Tony Award]]\n|[[Tony Award for Best Score|Best Score]]\n|''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2006\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[See What I Wanna See]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Lyrics|Outstanding Lyrics]]\n|''[[See What I Wanna See]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2012\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[Queen of the Mist]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Lyrics|Outstanding Lyrics]]\n|''[[Queen of the Mist]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Book of a Musical|Outstanding Book]]\n|''[[Queen of the Mist]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2013\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Lyrics|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|2016\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Music|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[First Daughter Suite]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|\n||[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Lyrics|Outstanding Music]]\n|''[[First Daughter Suite]]''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n|}\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Mordden |first=Ethan |authorlink=Ethan Mordden |title=The Happiest Corpse I've Ever Seen |year=2004 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York |isbn=0-312-23954-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/happiestcorpseiv00mord }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IBDB name|13016}}\n*[http://archives.nypl.org/the/23071 Michael John LaChiusa papers, 1970s-2015], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121006095038/http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=people&keyword=name&first=Michael&last=LaChiusa&middle=John  Internet Off-Broadway Database listing]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/american-theatre-wing/episode94 Michael John LaChiusa] - ''Downstage Center'' interview at [[American Theatre Wing|American Theatre Wing.org]]\n*[http://www.nodanw.com/composers/l-composers/lachiusa.html Composers and their stage works (Michael John LaChiusa)] <!--this is a mirror of Wikipedia, note the source listed at the bottom of the page-->\n\n{{Michael John LaChiusa}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lachiusa, Michael John}}\n[[Category:American musical theatre composers]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre lyricists]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT composers]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Chautauqua, New York]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:American opera librettists]]\n[[Category:American writers of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Michael John LaChiusa\n| image       = Michael John LaChiusa Headshot.jpg\n| caption     = Official publicity photo\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age |1962|07|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Chautauqua, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Composer, lyricist, librettist\n| genre       =\n| movement    =\n| period      = 1989\u2014present\n| signature   = \n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n}}\n'''Michael John LaChiusa''' (born July 24, 1962) is an [[United States|American]] [[musical theatre]] and [[opera]] [[composer]], [[lyricist]], and [[libretto|librettist]]. He is best known for musically esoteric shows such as ''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'', ''[[Marie Christine]]'', ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]'', and ''[[See What I Wanna See]]''.<ref name=\"feud\"/><ref name=\"post\"/> He was nominated for four [[Tony Award]]s in 2000 for his score and book for both ''Marie Christine'' and ''The Wild Party'' and received another nomination in 1996 for his work on the libretto for ''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold (musical)|Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]''.\n\n==Biography==\nLaChiusa grew up in [[Chautauqua, New York]], the eldest of three boys in an [[Italians|Italian]] [[Catholic]] family.  His parents had a \"[v]ery mentally abusive\" relationship; Michael was not close to his father, but was encouraged by his mother to pursue his interest in music.<ref name=\"somany\">Green, Jesse.  [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/05/theater/newsandfeatures/05gree.html?_r=1&scp=2&sq=%22so+many+musicals+to+write%22&st=nyt&oref=slogin \"So Many Musicals to Write, So Little Time\"], [[The New York Times]], 2006-03-05.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  He taught himself to play piano at the age of seven and had little formal music training.  LaChiusa was influenced early on by the music of \"modern American composers\" such as [[John Corigliano]], [[John Adams (composer)|John Adams]], and [[Philip Glass]], as well as the [[musical theatre]] composers [[George Gershwin]], [[Richard Rodgers]], and [[Stephen Sondheim]].<ref name=\"opera\">Blue, Robert Wilder.  [http://www.usoperaweb.com/2001/july/lachiusa1.htm \"Lovers and Friends\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20030116070551/http://www.usoperaweb.com/2001/july/lachiusa1.htm |date=2003-01-16 }}, USOperaWeb, June 2001.  Retrieved on 2008-03-01.</ref><ref>Heilpern, John.  [http://www.observer.com/node/47170 \"Worried About the War? Why Not Forget Your Troubles at Little Fish\"], [[The New York Observer]], 2003-03-03.  Retrieved on 2008-03-01.</ref>  LaChiusa graduated high school early and enrolled in a television journalism program, but he dropped out after a semester.<ref name=\"somany\"/><ref name=\"opera\"/>\n\nIn 1980, LaChiusa moved to New York City, where he took jobs as a music director and accompanist while trying to find songwriting work.  In the mid-1980s, he joined the [[BMI Lehman Engel Musical Theater Workshop]], where he was strongly influenced by a series of mentors and where he segued from writing \"camp\" songs to more serious work.<ref name=\"post\">Pressley, Nelson.  [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A9384-2004Oct29.html \"At Long Last, All Systems Are Gogh For 'Yellow': Composer LaChiusa's Difficult Musical Shapes Up\"], [[The Washington Post]], 2004-10-31.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  In 1993, [[The Public Theater]]'s producer [[George C. Wolfe]] presented LaChiusa's ''[[First Lady Suite]]''.  A year later, [[Lincoln Center]] produced his musical ''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'' [[Off Broadway]].  A series of interconnected stories about love based on [[Arthur Schnitzler]]'s play ''[[La Ronde (play)|La Ronde]]'', ''Hello Again'' was nominated for ten [[Drama Desk Award]]s, including three (Outstanding Book of a Musical, Outstanding Music, and Outstanding Lyrics) for LaChiusa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dramadesk.com/1993_1994dd.htm |title=Drama Desk Awards 2006 - Winners 2001 |publisher=Dramadesk.com |accessdate=2013-12-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20060424094843/http://dramadesk.com/1993_1994dd.htm |archivedate=2006-04-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, LaChiusa wrote additional book material for the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold (musical)|Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]'' (an adaptation of [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]'s [[Chronicle of a Death Foretold|1981 novella of the same name]].)  For the book, written with [[Graciela Daniele]] and [[Jim Lewis (librettist)|Jim Lewis]], LaChiusa received a [[Tony Award]] nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Book of a Musical|Best Book of a Musical]].\n\nDuring the 1999-2000 season, two of LaChiusa's large-scale musicals premiered on Broadway: ''[[Marie Christine]]'' and ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]''.  ''Marie Christine'', a retelling of the [[Medea]] myth set in 19th-century [[Louisiana]], starred [[Audra McDonald]] and attracted controversy due to its grim subject matter and demanding score\u2014''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that \"even the formidable and classically trained McDonald could sing it only six times a week, rather than the standard eight.\"<ref name=\"somany\"/>  ''Marie Christine'' closed after 42 performances; LaChiusa later said that the show \"in my mind should have been performed for three performances....  Only three.  It's huge, and it's intensely difficult\".<ref name=\"post\"/>  ''The Wild Party'' was based on the [[The Wild Party (poem)|1928 poem of the same name]] by [[Joseph Moncure March]] and starred [[Toni Collette]], [[Mandy Patinkin]], and [[Eartha Kitt]].  ''The Wild Party'' struggled commercially; after receiving seven Tony nominations but failing to win a single one, producers closed the show.<ref>McKinley, Jesse.  [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9400E7D9143FF934A35755C0A9669C8B63&scp=1&sq=%22the+wild+party%22+AND+%22tony%22+AND+%22miracle%22&st=nyt \"Shut Out of Tonys, ''The Wild Party'' Is Over\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 2000-06-07.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  For both ''Marie Christine'' and ''The Wild Party'', LaChiusa received Tony nominations for Best Book of a Musical and [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Little Fish (musical)|Little Fish]]'', an uncharacteristically cheerful one-act musical for LaChiusa, based on two short stories by [[Deborah Eisenberg]], premiered Off-Broadway.  The show's failure sent LaChiusa into a funk; he recalled, \"I went, 'My God, they don't want the hard stuff and more challenging material here in this city from me.  They don't want something nice and fun, either.  What am I supposed to do?'\"<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\nIn August 2005, LaChiusa published an article in ''[[Opera News]]'' that disparaged several successful, upbeat Broadway musicals of the 2000s, among them ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' and ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', which LaChiusa dubbed a \"faux-musical\".<ref name=\"feud\">[[Simonson, Robert]].  [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/11/theater/newsandfeatures/11spat.html \"2 Broadway Composers Do Inharmonious Battle\"], ''The New York Times'', 2005-08-11.  Retrieved on 2008-02-29.</ref>  He continued, \"Instead of choreography, there is dancing. Instead of crafted songwriting, there is tune-positioning. Faux-musicals are mechanical; they have to be. For expectations to be met, there can be no room for risk, derring-do or innovation.\"<ref name=\"feud\"/>  The article caused a great deal of controversy and provoked shocked responses from several of LaChiusa's colleagues, who saw it as an attack.<ref name=\"feud\"/>\n\nIn October 2005, LaChiusa's musical ''[[See What I Wanna See]]'', based on the stories \"In a Grove,\" \"The Dragon,\" and \"Kesa and Morito\" by [[Ry\u016bnosuke Akutagawa]], opened Off-Broadway at the Public Theater and closed on December 4, 2005.<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=4459 ''See What I Wanna See''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100111054906/http://www.lortel.org/LLA_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=4459 |date=2010-01-11 }} Internet Off-Broadway listing, accessed September 28, 2015</ref><ref name=\"somany\"/>  LaChiusa was nominated for Drama Desk Awards for Outstanding Music and Outstanding Lyrics.\n\nIn September 2008, he was quoted in ''[[Opera News]] Online'' as working on an adaptation of [[Bizet]]'s opera ''[[Carmen]]'' with [[Tony Award|Tony]] winner [[Audra McDonald]] in mind.<ref>Portantiere, Michael. [http://www.metoperafamily.org/operanews/issue/article.aspx?id=4980&issueID=325 \"Over the Borderline\"], [http://www.metoperafamily.org/operanews Opera News Online], September 2008, vol 73, no. 3. Retrieved on 2008-09-02.</ref> <!-- Did these happen?  If not, I suggest deleting the paragarph -->\n\nIn April 2009, the [[Signature Theatre (Arlington VA)|Signature Theatre]], [[Arlington, Virginia]], premiered ''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]'', a musical adaptation of [[Edna Ferber]]'s [[Giant (novel)|1952 novel of the same name]] with music and lyrics by LaChiusa and book by [[Sybille Pearson]], who wrote the book for the 1983 musical ''[[Baby (musical)|Baby]]''.<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/115609.html \"DC's Signature Theatre Will Premiere LaChiusa Musical Giant in 2009; Ace and Whistle Also on Schedule\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308134147/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/115609.html |date=2008-03-08 }}, [[Playbill]], 2008-03-04.  Retrieved on 2008-03-04.</ref>\n\n''[[Queen of the Mist]]'' is a musical adaption of the story of [[Annie Edson Taylor]], the first person to survive going over Niagara Falls in a barrel. Commissioned by Off-Broadway theatre company the [[Transport Group]] ''Queen of the Mist'' received a developmental lab in fall 2010, and opened in November 2011 at The Gym at Judson. With direction by Jack Cummings III and choreography by Scott Rink, the musical stars [[Mary Testa]] and [[Julia Murney]].<ref>Brantley, Ben.[http://theater.nytimes.com/2011/11/07/theater/reviews/queen-of-the-mist-at-the-gym-at-judson-review.html \"Theater Review:Obsessed With Taking the Plunge\"] ''The New York Times'', November 6, 2011</ref>\n\nLaChiusa's work, ''Nine Fathers of Ariel'', is \"a dance musical which centers on a mother's effort to provide her son with good fathering in the face of a war-obsessed world\".<ref name=nine/> It had a 29-hour private industry reading on April 5, 2014. It was a co-collaboration with Ellen Fitzhugh, with [[Graciela Daniele]] directing and musical direction by Mary Mitchell Campbell. The cast included [[Tonya Pinkins]], [[Marc Kudisch]], [[Malcolm Gets]], [[Telly Leung]], Bryce Ryness, [[Darius de Haas]], [[Stanley Bahorek]], Sydney James Harcourt, Ashley Robinson, Casey Robinson, and Hayley Feinstein.<ref name=nine>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/189570-Reading-of-Michael-John-LaChiusa-Ellen-Fitzhugh-Dance-Musical-to-Feature-Tonya-Pinkins-Marc-Kudisch-Malcolm-Gets-Telly-Leung-and-More \"Reading of Michael John LaChiusa Ellen Fitzhugh Dance Musical to Feature Tonya Pinkins Marc Kudisch Malcolm Gets Telly Leung and More\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407075958/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/189570-Reading-of-Michael-John-LaChiusa-Ellen-Fitzhugh-Dance-Musical-to-Feature-Tonya-Pinkins-Marc-Kudisch-Malcolm-Gets-Telly-Leung-and-More |date=2014-04-07 }} Playbill, April 2, 2014</ref>\n\nLaChiusa's musical ''[[First Daughter Suite]]'' premiered Off-Broadway at the Public Theater on October 6, 2015 (previews), and was directed by Kirsten Sanderson. He stated about the work: \"While he didn't want to fully imitate ''First Lady Suite'', LaChiusa felt that the new piece could be an extension of the earlier piece. It would not, however, be a sequel.\" The musical looks at the women in the lives of Presidents [[Richard Nixon]], [[Jimmy Carter]], [[Ronald Reagan]], [[George H. W. Bush]] and [[George W. Bush]].<ref>Fox, Jenna Tesse. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/why-michael-john-lachiusa-is-obsessed-with-exploring-unheard-stories-of-women-especially-in-the-white-house-364099# \"Why Michael John LaChiusa is \"Obsessed\" With Exploring Unheard Stories of Women \u2014 Especially in the White House\"] Playbill, September 28, 2015</ref> The women are: Patricia Nixon, played by [[Barbara Walsh]] and daughters Tricia played by Betsy Morgan and Julie played by Cassie Levy; Rosalynn Carter, played by Rachel Bay Jones and Amy Carter played by Carly Tamer; Betty Ford played by [[Alison Fraser]] and Susan Ford played by Betsy Morgan; Patti Davis played by Cassie Levy and mother Nancy Reagan, played by Alison Fraser; and Barbara Bush played by [[Mary Testa]] and daughter-in-law Laura played by Rachel Bay Jones.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/alison-fraser-rachel-bay-jones-caissie-levy-barbara-walsh-star-in-first-daughter-suite-beginning-tonight-365704# \"Alison Fraser, Rachel Bay Jones, Caissie Levy, Barbara Walsh Star in 'First Daughter Suite', Beginning Tonight\"] Playbill, October 6, 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.publictheater.org/Global/Press/2015/FirstDaughter_CompleteCasting.pdf \"'First Daughter Suite' Listing, Press Release\"] publictheater.org, accessed September 28, 2015</ref>\n\nThe world premiere of LaChiusa's musical ''Rain'' (book by [[Sybille Pearson]], based on the short story \"Rain\" by [[Somerset Maugham]]),  runs March 24-May 1, 2016 at San Diego's [[Old Globe Theatre]]. It is directed by [[Barry Edelstein]], and stars [[Eden Espinosa]] as Sadie Thompson.<ref name=globe>{{cite web|title=Rain |url=http://theoldglobe.org/tickets/production.aspx?PID=11875 |website=The Old Globe Theatre |accessdate=18 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315082450/http://theoldglobe.org/tickets/production.aspx?PID=11875 |archivedate=15 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>Viagas, Robert. [http://www.playbill.com/article/full-cast-announced-for-new-michael-john-lachiusa-musical-rain-com-384950# \"Full Cast Announced for New Michael John LaChiusa Musical 'Rain'\"] Playbill, February 2016</ref><ref>Viagas, Robert. [http://www.playbill.com/article/eden-espinosa-stars-in-today-39-s-world-premiere-of-michael-john-lachiusa-39-s-musical-rain-com-384950# \"Eden Espinosa Stars in Today's World Premiere of Michael John LaChiusa's Musical 'Rain'\"] Playbill, April 1, 2016</ref>\n\n===Teaching===\n[[File:MJLC Columbia College Master Class Photo.jpg|thumb|Michael John LaChiusa speaks to students after a performance of his musical [[Bernarda Alba (musical)]] at Columbia College.]]\nLaChiusa is an adjunct professor at the Graduate Musical Theatre Writing Program at the [[Tisch School of the Arts]] at [[New York University]].\n\n===Performing===\nLaChiusa also performs at various cabaret and concert venues, including:\n*''La La Chiusa'' at [[Joe's Pub]] (October 16, 2000 \u2013 November 5, 2000);<ref>[http://www.theatermania.com/new-york/shows/la-la-lachiusa_6453/ La La LaChiusa listing at Joes Pub, October-November 2000] theatermania.com, accessed July 27, 2009</ref>\n*''The Girly Show'', as part of [[Lincoln Center]]'s American Songbook Series (May 17, 2004)<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/Photo_Coverage_The_Girly_Show_a_Celebration_of_the_Music_of_Michael_John_La_Chiusa_20040519 \"Photo Coverage: 'The Girly Show' a Celebration of the Music of Michael John La Chiusa,\"] broadwayworld.com, May 19, 2004</ref> and at Cinespace, Hollywood (August 15, 2005);<ref>BWW News Desk. [http://broadwayworld.com/article/LaChiusa_Appears_at_Blanks_Gala_for_Girly_Show_Aug_15_20050809 \"LaChiusa Appears at Blank's Gala for Girly Show, Aug. 15,\"] broadwayworld.com, August 9, 2005</ref>\n*''Platform Series'' at [[Lincoln Center Theater]] (March 29, 2006);<ref>BWW News Desk. [http://broadwayworld.com/article/LaChiusa_Appears_at_LCT_as_Part_of_Platform_Series_March_29_20060329 \"LaChiusa Appears at LCT as Part of Platform Series, March 29,\"] broadwayworld.com, March 29, 2006;</ref>\n*''Little Fish in Concert'' at Joe's Pub (July 10, 2006);<ref>[http://www.theatermania.com/new-york/shows/little-fish_122785/ ''Little Fish'' in concert listing for July 10, 2006] theatermania.com, accessed July 27, 2009</ref>\n*Concert that featured music from ''Bernarda Alba'' and other LaChiusa scores as well as a ''Little Fish'' CD Release party ; Alice Ripley and Lea DeLaria, appeared at Joe's Pub (September 8, 2008);<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/120114-LaChiusa_to_Celebrate_Little_Fish_CD_with_Joe's_Pub_Concert LaChiusa to Celebrate Little Fish CD with Joe's Pub Concert,\"] playbill.com, August 5, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joespub.com/component/option,com_shows/task,view/Itemid,40/id,4085 |title=Michael John LaChiusa:Little Fish release concert listing for September 8, 2008 |publisher=Joespub.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref><ref>[http://shkbuzz.wordpress.com/2008/09/18/photo-moments-little-fish-at-joes-pub/  \"Photo Moments; Little Fish at Joe's Pub\"] shkbuzz.wordpress.com, September 18, 2008</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nIn 2004, LaChiusa told ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that he was a \"gay man, happily single\".<ref name=\"post\"/>\n\n==Work==\n\n===Broadway productions===\n*''[[Chronicle of a Death Foretold (musical)|Chronicle of a Death Foretold]]'' (additional book and lyrics with [[Graciela Daniele]] and Jim Lewis; music by [[Bob Telson]]) (1995)\n*''[[Marie Christine]]'' (1999)\n*''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]'' (book with [[George C. Wolfe]]) (2000)\n\n===Off-Broadway productions===\n*''[[First Lady Suite]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Hello Again (musical)|Hello Again]]'' (1994)\n*''The Petrified Prince'' (book by Edward Gallardo) (1994)\n*''[[Little Fish (musical)|Little Fish]]'' (2003)\n*''[[See What I Wanna See]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Bernarda Alba (musical)|Bernarda Alba]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Queen of the Mist]]'' (2011)<ref>[http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=5832 ''Queen of the Mist'' listing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525143949/http://www.lortel.org/lla_archive/index.cfm?search_by=show&id=5832 |date=2015-05-25 }} Internet Off-Broadway Database listing, accessed November 8, 2011</ref>\n*''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]'' (2012)\n*''[[First daughter suite|First Daughter Suite]]'' (2015)<ref>[http://www.publictheater.org/en/Public-Theater-Season/2015-2016-Season \"Public Theater 2015-2016 Season\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626185927/http://www.publictheater.org/en/Public-Theater-Season/2015-2016-Season/ |date=2015-06-26 }} public theater.org, accessed June 25, 2015</ref>\n\n===Other theatre===\n*''Bittersweet'', book, music and lyrics by Jerry Young; Boston, MA. Musical Director Michael Lachiusa. (1979)\n*''Buzzsaw Berkeley'', book by [[Doug Wright]], music and lyrics by LaChiusa; WPA Theater, New York City (1989)\n*''[[Broken Sleep]]'' book by [[Donald Margulies]], Williamstown Theatre Festival, Williamstown, MA, 3 plays with music (1997)<ref>Sommer, Elyse.[http://www.curtainup.com/brokensl.html \"CurtainUp Reviews Broken Sleep: Three Plays\"] curtainup.com, accessed July 27, 2009</ref>\n*''The Nutcracker'', new musical theatre version (translated into Japanese) of ''The Nutcracker'', book by [[Amon Miyamoto]], music and lyrics by LaChiusa; premiere in Tokyo (2001)<ref>LaChiusa, Michael.[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/07/theater/theater-making-sugar-plum-fairies-sing-sweetly-in-japanese.html?pagewanted=all  \"Theatre; Making Sugar Plum Fairies Sing, Sweetly, in Japanese,\"]''The New York Times'', July 7, 2002</ref>\n*''[[The Highest Yellow]]'', music and lyrics by LaChiusa, book by John Strand; musical commissioned and premiered by [[Signature Theatre (Arlington, Virginia)|Signature Theatre]] [[Arlington, Virginia]] (2004)<ref>Toscano, Michael.[http://www.theatermania.com/virginia/reviews/11-2004/the-highest-yellow_5321.html \"Review:''The Highest Yellow''\"], theatermania.com, November 9, 2004</ref>\n*''[[Hotel C'est L'Amour]]'', musical with music and lyrics by LaChiusa and conceived by Daniel Henning; premiere at The Blank Theatre Company, Los Angeles, California (2006)<ref>Hernandez, Ernio. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/102444-LaChiusa_Work_Hotel_C'est_L'Amour_with_Vicki_Lewis_Opens_in_L.A. \"LaChiusa Work Hotel C'est L'Amour with Vicki Lewis Opens in L.A.,\"] playbill.com, September 30, 2006</ref>\n*''[[Inner Voices: Solo Musicals]]'', three musicals in one act: Act 1 is ''Tres Ninas'', lyrics and music by Ellen Fitzhugh and LaChiusa; Zipper Theater, New York City (2008)<ref>Isherwood, Charles. [http://theater2.nytimes.com/2008/05/23/theater/reviews/23voic.html?partner=rssnyt&emc=rss \"Woman Troubles, in a Handy Musical Variety Pack\",] ''The New York Times'', May 23, 2008</ref>\n*''[[Giant (musical)|Giant]]'', music and lyrics by LaChiusa, book by [[Sybille Pearson]], Signature Theatre, Arlington, Virginia (2009)\n*''Los Otros'', book and lyrics by Ellen Fitzhugh, music by LaChiusa, directed by [[Graciela Daniele]], commissioned by Center Theatre Group; [[Mark Taper Forum]], Los Angeles, California (2012)<ref>Jones, Kenneth.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/166238-Michele-Pawk-and-Julio-Monge-Sing-Los-Otros-a-New-Musical-by-Michael-John-LaChiusa-and-Ellen-Fitzhugh \"Michele Pawk and Julio Monge Sing 'Los Otros', a New Musical by Michael John LaChiusa and Ellen Fitzhugh\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524194007/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/166238-Michele-Pawk-and-Julio-Monge-Sing-Los-Otros-a-New-Musical-by-Michael-John-LaChiusa-and-Ellen-Fitzhugh |date=2012-05-24 }} playbill.com, May 23, 2012</ref>\n*''Rain,'' book by [[Sybille Pearson]], music and lyrics by LaChiusa, directed by [[Barry Edelstein]], [[The Old Globe Theatre]], San Diego, California (2016)<ref name=globe/>\n\n===Opera, song cycles and other music===\n*''Four Short Operas: Break, Agnes, Eulogy For Mr. Hamm, Lucky Nurse'', book, music and lyrics by LaChiusa, [[Playwrights Horizons]] (14 performances) (1991)\n*''Desert of Roses'', libretto by LaChiusa, music by [[Robert Moran]], an opera commissioned and premiered by [[Houston Grand Opera]] (1992)<ref>[http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/desert_of_roses.htm \"''Desert of Roses'' information\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704170452/http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/desert_of_roses.htm |date=2008-07-04 }} members.macconnect.com</ref>\n*''[[From the Towers of the Moon]]'', libretto by LaChiusa, music by Robert Moran, an opera commissioned and premiered by [[Minnesota Opera]] (1992)<ref>[http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/from_the_towers_of_the_moon.htm \"''From the Towers of the Moon'' information\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011162847/http://members.macconnect.com/users/r/rbtmoran/from_the_towers_of_the_moon.htm |date=2008-10-11 }}, members.macconnect.com</ref>\n*''Tania'', libretto by LaChiusa, music by [[Anthony Davis (composer)|Anthony Davis]], Plays and Players Theater, New York City, and recorded (1992)<ref>Rothstein, Edward. [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/19/arts/review-opera-tania-cinque-and-the-super-bowl.html?pagewanted=all \"Review/Opera; Tania, Cinque and the Super Bowl,\"] ''The New York Times'', June 19, 1992</ref>\n*''Lovers and Friends (Chautauqua Variations)'', commissioned and performed by [[Lyric Opera of Chicago]], book, music and lyrics by LaChiusa (2001)<ref>Waleson, Heidi. [http://www.andante.com/article/article.cfm?id=13687&highlight=1&highlightterms=&lstKeywords= \"Chilly Scenes of Winter,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040228032852/http://www.andante.com/article/article.cfm?id=13687&highlight=1&highlightterms=&lstKeywords= |date=2004-02-28 }} andante.com, July 2001.</ref>\n*''The Seven Deadly Sins: A Song Cycle'', \"The Christian Thing to Do\", contribution to song cycle commissioned for [[Audra McDonald]], performed at [[Carnegie Hall]], New York City (2004)<!--an article on this work was deleted as a stub--><ref>Gans, Andrew.[https://archive.is/20130104150401/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/86517-Audra_McDonald_Premieres_The_Seven_Deadly_Sins_June_2_at_Zankel_Hall  \"Audra McDonald Premieres The Seven Deadly Sins June 2 at Zankel Hall\"], playbill.com, June 2, 2004</ref>\n*''The Cello Project'', chamber work for cello, part of a song cycle for Peter Sachon, cellist, premiered at the Leonard Nimoy Thalia at [[Symphony Space]], New York City (2005)<ref>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/91560-LaChiusa_Schwartz_Bucchino_Marzullo_and_More_Write_Cello_Pieces_for_March_7_Concert \"LaChiusa, Schwartz, Bucchino, Marzullo and More Write Cello Pieces for March 7 Concert,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629231753/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/91560-LaChiusa_Schwartz_Bucchino_Marzullo_and_More_Write_Cello_Pieces_for_March_7_Concert |date=2009-06-29 }} playbill.com, March 7, 2005</ref>\n*''pre.view'', choreography by [[Taye Diggs]] and Andrew Palermo, music by LaChiusa, Ailey Citigroup Theater, New York City (2006)<ref>Hernandez, Ernio. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/97673-Broadway%27s_Diggs_and_Palermo_Create_Dance_Play_pre.view_with_LaChiusa_Music \"Broadway's Diggs and Palermo Create Dance Play pre.view with LaChiusa Music,\"] playbill.com, January 31, 2006</ref>\n*''Send (who are you? i love you)'' music and libretto by LaChiusa, co-conceived by LaChiusa and Lonny Price for [[Audra McDonald]], performed by McDonald with Houston Grand Opera (2006)<ref>Gans, Andrew.  [https://archive.is/20120908085048/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/98256-Audra_McDonald_Makes_Houston_Grand_Opera_Debut_March_4 \"Audra McDonald Makes Houston Grand Opera Debut March 4,\"] playbill.com, March 4, 2006</ref>\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Wonder Pets]]'': LaChiusa wrote music for 15 episodes of this animated series (2006\u201307)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0775407/fullcredits Internet Movie Database listing for ''Wonder Pets'', credits] imdb.com</ref>\n*''Broadway: The Golden Age'': LaChiusa was one of many Broadway insiders interviewed for this documentary (2003)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0303797/ \"Broadway: The Golden Age\" listing] imdb.com</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Association\n!Category\n!Title\n!Result\n|-\n|1994\n|[[Drama Desk Award]]\n|[[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Lyrics|Outstanding Lyrics]]\n